# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nuclear-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The **atomic nucleus** is the small, dense region consisting of protons and neutrons at the center of an atom, discovered in 1911 by Ernest Rutherford at the University of Manchester based on the 1909 Geiger–Marsden gold foil experiment.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] After the discovery of the neutron in 1932, models for a nucleus composed of protons and neutrons were quickly developed by Dmitri Ivanenko and Werner Heisenberg.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] An atom is composed of a positively charged nucleus, with a cloud of negatively charged electrons surrounding it, bound together by electrostatic force.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Almost all of the mass of an atom is located in the nucleus, with a very small contribution from the electron cloud.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Protons and neutrons are bound together to form a nucleus by the nuclear force.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The diameter of the nucleus is in the range of 1.70 fm (1.70×10−15 m) for hydrogen (the diameter of a single proton) to about 11.7 fm for uranium.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] These dimensions are much smaller than the diameter of the atom itself (nucleus + electron cloud), by a factor of about 27,000 (uranium's atomic radius is about 156 pm (156×10−12 m)) to about 60,000 (hydrogen's atomic radius is about 52.92 pm).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The branch of physics involved with the study and understanding of the atomic nucleus, including its composition and the forces that bind it together, is called nuclear physics.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The nucleus was discovered in 1911, as a result of Ernest Rutherford's efforts to test Thomson's "plum pudding model" of the atom.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The electron had already been discovered by J.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Knowing that atoms are electrically neutral, J.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Thomson postulated that there must be a positive charge as well.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] In his plum pudding model, Thomson suggested that an atom consisted of negative electrons randomly scattered within a sphere of positive charge.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Ernest Rutherford later devised an experiment with his research partner Hans Geiger and with help of Ernest Marsden, that involved the deflection of alpha particles (helium nuclei) directed at a thin sheet of metal foil.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Thomson's model were correct, the positively charged alpha particles would easily pass through the foil with very little deviation in their paths, as the foil should act as electrically neutral if the negative and positive charges are so intimately mixed as to make it appear neutral.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] To his surprise, many of the particles were deflected at very large angles.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Because the mass of an alpha particle is about 8,000 times that of an electron, it became apparent that a very strong force must be present if it could deflect the massive and fast moving alpha particles.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] He realized that the plum pudding model could not be accurate and that the deflections of the alpha particles could only be explained if the positive and negative charges were separated from each other and that the mass of the atom was a concentrated point of positive charge.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] This justified the idea of a nuclear atom with a dense center of positive charge and mass.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The term **nucleus** is from the Latin word *nucleus*, a diminutive of *nux* ('nut'), meaning 'the kernel' (i.e., the 'small nut') inside a watery type of fruit (like a peach).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] In 1844, Michael Faraday used the term to refer to the "central point of an atom".
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The modern atomic meaning was proposed by Ernest Rutherford in 1912.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The adoption of the term "nucleus" to atomic theory, however, was not immediate.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Lewis stated, in his famous article *The Atom and the Molecule*, that "the atom is composed of the *kernel* and an outer atom or *shell.*" Similarly, the term *kern* meaning kernel is used for nucleus in German and Dutch.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The nucleus of an atom consists of neutrons and protons, which in turn are the manifestation of more elementary particles, called quarks, that are held in association by the nuclear strong force in certain stable combinations of hadrons, called baryons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The nuclear strong force extends far enough from each baryon so as to bind the neutrons and protons together against the repulsive electrical force between the positively charged protons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The nuclear strong force has a very short range, and essentially drops to zero just beyond the edge of the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The collective action of the positively charged nucleus is to hold the electrically negative charged electrons in their orbits about the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The collection of negatively charged electrons orbiting the nucleus display an affinity for certain configurations and numbers of electrons that make their orbits stable.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Which chemical element an atom represents is determined by the number of protons in the nucleus; the neutral atom will have an equal number of electrons orbiting that nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Individual chemical elements can create more stable electron configurations by combining to share their electrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] It is that sharing of electrons to create stable electronic orbits about the nuclei that appears to us as the chemistry of our macro world.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Protons define the entire charge of a nucleus, and hence its chemical identity.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Neutrons are electrically neutral, but contribute to the mass of a nucleus to nearly the same extent as the protons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Neutrons can explain the phenomenon of isotopes (same atomic number with different atomic mass).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The main role of neutrons is to reduce electrostatic repulsion inside the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Protons and neutrons are fermions, with different values of the strong isospin quantum number, so two protons and two neutrons can share the same space wave function since they are not identical quantum entities.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] They are sometimes viewed as two different quantum states of the same particle, the *nucleon*.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Two fermions, such as two protons, or two neutrons, or a proton + neutron (the deuteron) can exhibit bosonic behavior when they become loosely bound in pairs, which have integer spin.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] In the rare case of a hypernucleus, a third baryon called a hyperon, containing one or more strange quarks and/or other unusual quark(s), can also share the wave function.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] However, this type of nucleus is extremely unstable and not found on Earth except in high-energy physics experiments.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The shape of the atomic nucleus can be spherical, rugby ball-shaped (prolate deformation), discus-shaped (oblate deformation), triaxial (a combination of oblate and prolate deformation) or pear-shaped.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Nuclei are bound together by the residual strong force (nuclear force).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The residual strong force is a minor residuum of the strong interaction, which binds quarks together to form protons and neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The nuclear force is highly attractive at the distance of typical nucleon separation, and this overwhelms the repulsion between protons due to the electromagnetic force, thus allowing nuclei to exist.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] However, the residual strong force has a limited range because it decays quickly with distance (see Yukawa potential); thus only nuclei smaller than a certain size can be completely stable.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The largest known completely stable nucleus (i.e. stable to alpha, beta, and gamma decay) is lead-208 which contains a total of 208 nucleons (126 neutrons and 82 protons).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Nuclei larger than this maximum are unstable and tend to be increasingly short-lived with larger numbers of nucleons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] However, bismuth-209 is also stable to beta decay and has the longest half-life to alpha decay of any known isotope, estimated at a billion times longer than the age of the universe.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The residual strong force is effective over a very short range (usually only a few femtometres (fm); roughly one or two nucleon diameters) and causes an attraction between any pair of nucleons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] For example, between a proton and a neutron to form a deuteron [NP], and also between protons and protons, and neutrons and neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Halo nuclei form at the extreme edges of the chart of the nuclides—the neutron drip line and proton drip line—and are all unstable with short half-lives, measured in milliseconds; for example, lithium-11 has a half-life of 8.8 ms.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Halos in effect represent an excited state with nucleons in an outer quantum shell which has unfilled energy levels "below" it (both in terms of radius and energy).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The halo may be made of either neutrons [nn, nnn] or protons [pp, ppp].
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Nuclei which have a single neutron halo include 11Be and 19C.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] A two-neutron halo is exhibited by 6He, 11Li, 17B, 19B and 22C.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Two-neutron halo nuclei break into three fragments, never two, and are called *Borromean nuclei* because of this behavior (referring to a system of three interlocked rings in which breaking any ring frees both of the others).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] 8He and 14Be both exhibit a four-neutron halo.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Nuclei which have a proton halo include 8B and 26P.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] A two-proton halo is exhibited by 17Ne and 27S.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Proton halos are expected to be more rare and unstable than the neutron examples, because of the repulsive electromagnetic forces of the halo proton(s).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Although the Standard Model of physics is widely believed to completely describe the composition and behavior of the nucleus, generating predictions from theory is much more difficult than for most other areas of particle physics.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Historically, experiments have been compared to relatively crude models that are necessarily imperfect.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] None of these models can completely explain experimental data on nuclear structure.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The nuclear radius (*R*) is considered to be one of the basic quantities that any model must predict.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] where *A* = Atomic mass number (the number of protons *Z*, plus the number of neutrons *N*) and *r*0 = 1.25 fm = 1.25×10−15 m.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] In this equation, the "constant" *r*0 varies by 0.2 fm, depending on the nucleus in question, but this is less than 20% change from a constant.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] In other words, packing protons and neutrons in the nucleus gives *approximately* the same total size result as packing hard spheres of a constant size (like marbles) into a tight spherical or almost spherical bag (some stable nuclei are not quite spherical, but are known to be prolate).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The cluster model describes the nucleus as a molecule-like collection of proton-neutron groups (e.g., alpha particles) with one or more valence neutrons occupying molecular orbitals.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Early models of the nucleus viewed the nucleus as a rotating liquid drop.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] In this model, the trade-off of long-range electromagnetic forces and relatively short-range nuclear forces, together cause behavior which resembled surface tension forces in liquid drops of different sizes.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The terms in the semi-empirical mass formula, which can be used to approximate the binding energy of many nuclei, are considered as the sum of five types of energies (see below).
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] A number of models for the nucleus have also been proposed in which nucleons occupy orbitals, much like the atomic orbitals in atomic physics theory.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] These wave models imagine nucleons to be either sizeless point particles in potential wells, or else probability waves as in the "optical model", frictionlessly orbiting at high speed in potential wells.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] In the above models, the nucleons may occupy orbitals in pairs, due to being fermions, which allows explanation of even/odd *Z* and *N* effects well known from experiments.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The exact nature and capacity of nuclear shells differs from those of electrons in atomic orbitals, primarily because the potential well in which the nucleons move (especially in larger nuclei) is quite different from the central electromagnetic potential well which binds electrons in atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Some resemblance to atomic orbital models may be seen in a small atomic nucleus like that of helium-4, in which the two protons and two neutrons separately occupy 1s orbitals analogous to the 1s orbital for the two electrons in the helium atom, and achieve unusual stability for the same reason.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Nuclei with 5 nucleons are all extremely unstable and short-lived, yet, helium-3, with 3 nucleons, is very stable even with lack of a closed 1s orbital shell.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Another nucleus with 3 nucleons, the triton hydrogen-3 is unstable and will decay into helium-3 when isolated.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Weak nuclear stability with 2 nucleons {NP} in the 1s orbital is found in the deuteron hydrogen-2, with only one nucleon in each of the proton and neutron potential wells.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] While each nucleon is a fermion, the {NP} deuteron is a boson and thus does not follow Pauli Exclusion for close packing within shells.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Lithium-6 with 6 nucleons is highly stable without a closed second 1p shell orbital.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] For light nuclei with total nucleon numbers 1 to 6 only those with 5 do not show some evidence of stability.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Observations of beta-stability of light nuclei outside closed shells indicate that nuclear stability is much more complex than simple closure of shell orbitals with magic numbers of protons and neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] For larger nuclei, the shells occupied by nucleons begin to differ significantly from electron shells, but nevertheless, present nuclear theory does predict the magic numbers of filled nuclear shells for both protons and neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] The closure of the stable shells predicts unusually stable configurations, analogous to the noble group of nearly-inert gases in chemistry.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] An example is the stability of the closed shell of 50 protons, which allows tin to have 10 stable isotopes, more than any other element.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Similarly, the distance from shell-closure explains the unusual instability of isotopes which have far from stable numbers of these particles, such as the radioactive elements 43 (technetium) and 61 (promethium), each of which is preceded and followed by 17 or more stable elements.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] There are however problems with the shell model when an attempt is made to account for nuclear properties well away from closed shells.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] This has led to complex *post hoc* distortions of the shape of the potential well to fit experimental data, but the question remains whether these mathematical manipulations actually correspond to the spatial deformations in real nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Problems with the shell model have led some to propose realistic two-body and three-body nuclear force effects involving nucleon clusters and then build the nucleus on this basis.
[src:nuclear-physics/atomic-nucleus] Three such cluster models are the 1936 resonating group structure model of John Wheeler, close-packed spheron model of Linus Pauling and the 2D Ising model of MacGregor.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] In physics and chemistry, **binding energy** is the smallest amount of energy required to remove a particle from a system of particles or to disassemble a system of particles into individual parts.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] In the former meaning the term is predominantly used in condensed matter physics, atomic physics, and chemistry, whereas in nuclear physics the term *separation energy* is used.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] A bound system is typically at a lower energy level than its unbound constituents.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] According to relativity theory, a Δ*E* decrease in the total energy of a system is accompanied by a decrease Δ*m* in the total mass, where Δ*mc*2 = Δ*E*.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] There are several types of binding energy, each operating over a different distance and energy scale.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] The smaller the size of a bound system, the higher its associated binding energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] A bound system is typically at a lower energy level than its unbound constituents because its mass must be less than the total mass of its unbound constituents.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] For systems with low binding energies, this "lost" mass after binding may be fractionally small, whereas for systems with high binding energies, the missing mass may be an easily measurable fraction.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This missing mass may be lost during the process of binding as energy in the form of heat or light, with the removed energy corresponding to the removed mass through Einstein's equation *E* = *mc*2.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] In the process of binding, the constituents of the system might enter higher energy states of the nucleus/atom/molecule while retaining their mass, and because of this, it is necessary that they are removed from the system before its mass can decrease.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] Once the system cools to normal temperatures and returns to ground states regarding energy levels, it will contain less mass than when it first combined and was at high energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This loss of heat represents the "mass deficit", and the heat itself retains the mass that was lost (from the point of view of the initial system).
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This mass will appear in any other system that absorbs the heat and gains thermal energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] For example, if two objects are attracting each other in space through their gravitational field, the attraction force accelerates the objects, increasing their velocity, which converts their potential energy (gravity) into kinetic energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] When the particles either pass through each other without interaction or elastically repel during the collision, the gained kinetic energy (related to speed) begins to revert into potential energy, driving the collided particles apart.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] The decelerating particles will return to the initial distance and beyond into infinity, or stop and repeat the collision (oscillation takes place).
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This shows that the system, which loses no energy, does not combine (bind) into a solid object, parts of which oscillate at short distances.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] Therefore, to bind the particles, the kinetic energy gained due to the attraction must be dissipated by resistive force.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] Complex objects in collision ordinarily undergo inelastic collision, transforming some kinetic energy into internal energy (heat content, which is atomic movement), which is further radiated in the form of photons – the light and heat.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] Once the energy to escape the gravity is dissipated in the collision, the parts will oscillate at a closer, possibly atomic, distance, thus looking like one solid object.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This lost energy, necessary to overcome the potential barrier to separate the objects, is the binding energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] If this binding energy were retained in the system as heat, its mass would not decrease, whereas binding energy lost from the system as heat radiation would itself have mass.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] It directly represents the "mass deficit" of the cold, bound system.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] Closely analogous considerations apply in chemical and nuclear reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] Exothermic chemical reactions in closed systems do not change mass, but do become less massive once the heat of reaction is removed, though this mass change is too small to measure with standard equipment.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] In nuclear reactions, the fraction of mass that may be removed as light or heat, i.e. binding energy, is often a much larger fraction of the system mass.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] It may thus be measured directly as a mass difference between rest masses of reactants and (cooled) products.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This is because nuclear forces are comparatively stronger than the Coulombic forces associated with the interactions between electrons and protons that generate heat in chemistry.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] Mass change (decrease) in bound systems, particularly atomic nuclei, has also been termed *mass defect*, *mass deficit*, or mass *packing fraction*.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] The difference between the unbound system calculated mass and experimentally measured mass of nucleus (mass change) is denoted as Δ*m*.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] After a nuclear reaction occurs that results in an excited nucleus, the energy that must be radiated or otherwise removed as binding energy in order to decay to the unexcited state may be in one of several forms.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This may be electromagnetic waves, such as gamma radiation; the kinetic energy of an ejected particle, such as an electron, in internal conversion decay; or partly as the rest mass of one or more emitted particles, such as the particles of beta decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] No mass deficit can appear, in theory, until this radiation or this energy has been emitted and is no longer part of the system.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] When nucleons bind together to form a nucleus, they must lose a small amount of mass, i.e. there is a change in mass to stay bound.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This mass change must be released as various types of photon or other particle energy as above, according to the relation *E* = *mc*2.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] Thus, after the binding energy has been removed, **binding energy = mass change × *c*2**.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This energy is a measure of the forces that hold the nucleons together.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] It represents energy that must be resupplied from the environment for the nucleus to be broken up into individual nucleons.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] For example, an atom of deuterium has a mass defect of 0.0023884 Da, and its binding energy is nearly equal to 2.23 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This means that energy of 2.23 MeV is required to disintegrate an atom of deuterium.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] The energy given off during either nuclear fusion or nuclear fission is the difference of the binding energies of the "fuel", i.e. the initial nuclide(s), from that of the fission or fusion products.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] In practice, this energy may also be calculated from the substantial mass differences between the fuel and products, which uses previous measurements of the atomic masses of known nuclides, which always have the same mass for each species.
[src:nuclear-physics/binding-energy] This mass difference appears once evolved heat and radiation have been removed, which is required for measuring the (rest) masses of the (non-excited) nuclides involved in such calculations.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Nuclear fission was discovered by chemists Otto Hahn and Fritz Strassmann and physicists Lise Meitner and Otto Robert Frisch.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Hahn and Strassmann proved that a fission reaction had taken place on 19 December 1938, and Meitner and her nephew Frisch explained it theoretically in January 1939.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Frisch named the process "fission" by analogy with biological fission of living cells; according to Richard Rhodes, the idea arose in a discussion with physicist William A.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] In their second publication on nuclear fission in February 1939, Hahn and Strassmann predicted the existence and liberation of additional neutrons during the fission process, opening up the possibility of a nuclear chain reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] For heavy nuclides, it is an exothermic reaction which releases large amounts of energy both as electromagnetic radiation and as kinetic energy of the fragments (heating the bulk material where fission takes place).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Like nuclear fusion, for fission to produce energy, the total binding energy of the resulting elements must be greater than that of the starting element.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The fission barrier must also be overcome.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Fissionable nuclides primarily split in interactions with fast neutrons, while fissile nuclides easily split in interactions with "slow" i.e. thermal neutrons, usually originating from moderation of fast neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Fission is a form of nuclear transmutation because the resulting fragments (or daughter atoms) are not the same element as the original parent atom.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The two (or more) nuclei produced are most often of comparable but slightly different sizes, typically with a mass ratio of products of about 3 to 2, for common fissile isotopes.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Most fissions are binary fissions (producing two charged fragments), but occasionally (2 to 4 times per 1000 events), *three* positively charged fragments are produced, in a ternary fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The smallest of these fragments in ternary processes ranges in size from a proton to an argon nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Spontaneous fission was discovered in 1940 by Flyorov, Petrzhak, and Kurchatov in Moscow.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] In contrast to nuclear fusion, which drives the formation of stars and their development, one can consider nuclear fission as negligible for the evolution of the universe.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Nonetheless, natural nuclear fission reactors may form under very rare conditions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Accordingly, all elements (with a few exceptions, see "spontaneous fission") which are important for the formation of solar systems, planets and also for all forms of life are not fission products, but rather the results of fusion processes.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The unpredictable composition of the products (which vary in a broad probabilistic and somewhat chaotic manner) distinguishes fission from purely quantum tunneling processes such as proton emission, alpha decay, and cluster decay, which give the same products each time.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Nuclear fission produces energy for nuclear power and drives the explosion of nuclear weapons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Both uses are possible because certain substances called nuclear fuels undergo fission when struck by fission neutrons, and in turn emit neutrons when they break apart.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This makes a self-sustaining nuclear chain reaction possible, releasing energy at a controlled rate in a nuclear reactor or at a very rapid, uncontrolled rate in a nuclear weapon.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The amount of free energy released in the fission of an equivalent amount of 235 U is a million times more than that released in the combustion of methane or from hydrogen fuel cells.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The products of nuclear fission, however, are on average far more radioactive than the heavy elements which are normally fissioned as fuel, and remain so for significant amounts of time, giving rise to a nuclear waste problem.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] However, the seven long-lived fission products make up only a small fraction of fission products.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Neutron absorption which does not lead to fission produces plutonium (from 238 U) and minor actinides (from both 235 U and 238 U) whose radiotoxicity is far higher than that of the long lived fission products.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Concerns over nuclear waste accumulation and the destructive potential of nuclear weapons are a counterbalance to the peaceful desire to use fission as an energy source.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The thorium fuel cycle produces virtually no plutonium and much less minor actinides, but 232 U - or rather its decay products - are a major gamma ray emitter.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] All actinides are fertile or fissile and fast breeder reactors can fission them all albeit only in certain configurations.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Nuclear reprocessing aims to recover usable material from spent nuclear fuel to both enable uranium (and thorium) supplies to last longer and to reduce the amount of "waste".
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The industry term for a process that fissions all or nearly all actinides is a "closed fuel cycle".
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Younes and Loveland define fission as, "...a collective motion of the protons and neutrons that make up the nucleus, and as such it is distinguishable from other phenomena that break up the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Nuclear fission is an extreme example of large-amplitude collective motion that results in the division of a parent nucleus into two or more fragment nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Nuclear fission can occur without neutron bombardment as a type of radioactive decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This type of fission is called spontaneous fission, and was first observed in 1940.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] During induced fission, a compound system is formed after an incident particle fuses with a target.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The resultant excitation energy may be sufficient to emit neutrons, or gamma-rays, and nuclear scission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Fission into two fragments is called binary fission, and is the most common nuclear reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Occurring least frequently is ternary fission, in which a third particle is emitted.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This third particle is commonly an α particle.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Since in nuclear fission, the nucleus emits more neutrons than the one it absorbs, a chain reaction is possible.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Binary fission may produce any of the fission products, at 95±15 and 135±15 daltons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] However, the binary process happens merely because it is the most probable.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] In anywhere from two to four fissions per 1000 in a nuclear reactor, ternary fission can produce three positively charged fragments (plus neutrons) and the smallest of these may range from so small a charge and mass as a proton (*Z* = 1), to as large a fragment as argon (*Z* = 18).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The most common small fragments, however, are composed of 90% helium-4 nuclei with more energy than alpha particles from alpha decay (so-called "long range alphas" at ~16 megaelectronvolts (MeV)), plus helium-6 nuclei, and tritons (the nuclei of tritium).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Though less common than binary fission, it still produces significant helium-4 and tritium gas buildup in the fuel rods of modern nuclear reactors.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Bohr and Wheeler used their liquid drop model, the packing fraction curve of Arthur Jeffrey Dempster, and Eugene Feenberg's estimates of nucleus radius and surface tension, to estimate the mass differences of parent and daughters in fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] They then equated this mass difference to energy using Einstein's mass-energy equivalence formula.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The stimulation of the nucleus after neutron bombardment was analogous to the vibrations of a liquid drop, with surface tension and the Coulomb force in opposition.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Plotting the sum of these two energies as a function of elongated shape, they determined the resultant energy surface had a saddle shape.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The saddle provided an energy barrier called the critical energy barrier.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Energy of about 6 MeV provided by the incident neutron was necessary to overcome this barrier and cause the nucleus to fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] According to John Lilley, "The energy required to overcome the barrier to fission is called the *activation energy* or *fission barrier* and is about 6 MeV for *A* ≈ 240.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] It is found that the activation energy decreases as A increases.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Maria Goeppert Mayer later proposed the nuclear shell model for the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The nuclides that can sustain a fission chain reaction are suitable for use as nuclear fuels.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The most common nuclear fuels are 235U (the isotope of uranium with mass number 235 and of use in nuclear reactors) and 239Pu (the isotope of plutonium with mass number 239).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] These fuels break apart into a bimodal range of chemical elements with atomic masses centering near 95 and 135 daltons (fission products).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Most nuclear fuels undergo spontaneous fission only very slowly, decaying instead mainly via an alpha-beta decay chain over periods of millennia to eons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] In a nuclear reactor or nuclear weapon, the overwhelming majority of fission events are induced by bombardment with another particle, a neutron, which is itself produced by prior fission events.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Fissionable isotopes such as uranium-238 require additional energy provided by fast neutrons (such as those produced by nuclear fusion in thermonuclear weapons).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] While *some* of the neutrons released from the fission of 238 U are fast enough to induce another fission in 238 U, *most* are not, meaning it can never achieve criticality.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] While there is a very small (albeit nonzero) chance of a thermal neutron inducing fission in 238 U, neutron absorption is orders of magnitude more likely.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Fission cross sections are a measurable property related to the probability that fission will occur in a nuclear reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Cross sections are a function of incident neutron energy, and those for 235 U and 239 Pu are a million times higher than 238 U at lower neutron energy levels.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Absorption of any neutron makes available to the nucleus binding energy of about 5.3 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] 238 U needs a fast neutron to supply the additional 1 MeV needed to cross the critical energy barrier for fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] In the case of 235 U however, that extra energy is provided when 235 U adjusts from an odd to an even mass.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] About 6 MeV of the fission-input energy is supplied by the simple binding of an extra neutron to the heavy nucleus via the strong force; however, in many fissionable isotopes, this amount of energy is not enough for fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Uranium-238, for example, has a near-zero fission cross section for neutrons of less than 1 MeV energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] If no additional energy is supplied by any other mechanism, the nucleus will not fission, but will merely absorb the neutron, as happens when 238 U absorbs slow and even some fraction of fast neutrons, to become 239 U.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The remaining energy to initiate fission can be supplied by two other mechanisms: one of these is more kinetic energy of the incoming neutron, which is increasingly able to fission a fissionable heavy nucleus as it exceeds a kinetic energy of 1 MeV or more (so-called fast neutrons).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Such high energy neutrons are able to fission 238 U directly (see thermonuclear weapon for application, where the fast neutrons are supplied by nuclear fusion).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] However, this process cannot happen to a great extent in a nuclear reactor, as too small a fraction of the fission neutrons produced by any type of fission have enough energy to efficiently fission 238 U.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Among the heavy actinide elements, however, those isotopes that have an odd number of neutrons (such as 235U with 143 neutrons) bind an extra neutron with an additional 1 to 2 MeV of energy over an isotope of the same element with an even number of neutrons (such as 238U with 146 neutrons).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This extra binding energy is made available as a result of the mechanism of neutron pairing effects, which itself is caused by the Pauli exclusion principle, allowing an extra neutron to occupy the same nuclear orbital as the last neutron in the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] In such isotopes, therefore, no neutron kinetic energy is needed, for all the necessary energy is supplied by absorption of any neutron, either of the slow or fast variety (the former are used in moderated nuclear reactors, and the latter are used in fast-neutron reactors, and in weapons).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] After an incident particle has fused with a parent nucleus, if the excitation energy is sufficient, the nucleus breaks into fragments.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This is called scission, and occurs at about 10−20 seconds.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The fragments can emit prompt neutrons at between 10−18 and 10−15 seconds.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] At about 10−11 seconds, the fragments can emit gamma rays.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] At 10−3 seconds β decay, β-delayed neutrons, and gamma rays are emitted from the decay products.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Typical fission events release about two hundred million eV (200 MeV) of energy for each fission event.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The exact isotope which is fissioned, and whether or not it is fissionable or fissile, has only a small impact on the amount of energy released.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This can be easily seen by examining the curve of binding energy (image below), and noting that the average binding energy of the actinide nuclides beginning with uranium is around 7.6 MeV per nucleon.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Looking further left on the curve of binding energy, where the fission products cluster, it is easily observed that the binding energy of the fission products tends to center around 8.5 MeV per nucleon.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Thus, in any fission event of an isotope in the actinide mass range, roughly 0.9 MeV are released per nucleon of the starting element.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The fission of 235U by a slow neutron yields nearly identical energy to the fission of 238U by a fast neutron.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This energy release profile holds for thorium and the various minor actinides as well.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] When a uranium nucleus fissions into two daughter nuclei fragments, about 0.1 percent of the mass of the uranium nucleus appears as the fission energy of ~200 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] For uranium-235 (total mean fission energy 202.79 MeV), typically ~169 MeV appears as the kinetic energy of the daughter nuclei, which fly apart at about 3% of the speed of light, due to Coulomb repulsion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Also, an average of 2.5 neutrons are emitted, with a mean kinetic energy per neutron of ~2 MeV (total of 4.8 MeV).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The fission reaction also releases ~7 MeV in prompt gamma ray photons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Some processes involving neutrons are notable for absorbing or finally yielding energy — for example neutron kinetic energy does not yield heat immediately if the neutron is captured by a uranium-238 atom to breed plutonium-239, but this energy is emitted if the plutonium-239 is later fissioned.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Without their existence, the nuclear chain-reaction would be prompt critical and increase in size faster than it could be controlled by human intervention.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] If these delayed neutrons are captured without producing fissions, they produce heat as well.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The binding energy of the nucleus is the difference between the rest-mass energy of the nucleus and the rest-mass energy of the neutron and proton nucleons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The binding energy formula includes volume, surface and Coulomb energy terms that include empirically derived coefficients for all three, plus energy ratios of a deformed nucleus relative to a spherical form for the surface and Coulomb terms.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Additional terms can be included such as symmetry, pairing, the finite range of the nuclear force, and charge distribution within the nuclei to improve the estimate.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Normally binding energy is referred to and plotted as average binding energy per nucleon.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Thus, the mass of an atom is less than the mass of its constituent protons and neutrons, assuming the average binding energy of its electrons is negligible.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The binding energy **B** is expressed in energy units, using Einstein's mass-energy equivalence relationship.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The binding energy also provides an estimate of the total energy released from fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The curve of binding energy is characterized by a broad maximum near mass number 60 at 8.6 MeV, then gradually decreases to 7.6 MeV at the highest mass numbers.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] At the lighter end of the scale, peaks are noted for helium-4, and the multiples such as beryllium-8, carbon-12, oxygen-16, neon-20 and magnesium-24.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Binding energy due to the nuclear force approaches a constant value for large **A**, while the Coulomb acts over a larger distance so that electrical potential energy per proton grows as **Z** increases.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Fission energy is released when a **A** is larger than approx.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Fusion energy is released when lighter nuclei combine.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] According to Lilley, "For all naturally occurring nuclei, the surface-energy term dominates and the nucleus exists in a state of equilibrium." The negative contribution of Coulomb energy arises from the repulsive electric force of the protons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The symmetry term arises from the fact that effective forces in the nucleus are stronger for unlike neutron-proton pairs, rather than like neutron–neutron or proton–proton pairs.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The pairing term arises from the fact that like nucleons form spin-zero pairs in the same spatial state.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The pairing is positive if **N** and **Z** are both even, adding to the binding energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] In fission there is a preference for fission fragments with even **Z**, which is called the odd–even effect on the fragments' charge distribution.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This can be seen in the empirical fragment yield data for each fission product, as products with even **Z** have higher yield values.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] However, no odd–even effect is observed on fragment distribution based on their **A**.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This result is attributed to nucleon pair breaking.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Stable nuclei, and unstable nuclei with very long half-lives, follow a trend of stability evident when **Z** is plotted against **N**.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] For lighter nuclei less than **N** = 20, the line has the slope **N** = **Z**, while the heavier nuclei require additional neutrons to remain stable.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Nuclei that are neutron- or proton-rich have excessive binding energy for stability, and the excess energy may convert a neutron to a proton or a proton to a neutron via the weak nuclear force, a process known as beta decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Neutron-induced fission of U-235 emits a total energy of 207 MeV, of which about 200 MeV is recoverable, Prompt fission fragments amount to 168 MeV, which are easily stopped with a fraction of a millimeter.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Prompt neutrons total 5 MeV, and this energy is recovered as heat via scattering in the reactor.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] However, many fission fragments are neutron-rich and decay via β− emissions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] According to Lilley, "The radioactive decay energy from the fission chains is the second release of energy due to fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] John Lilley states, "...neutron-induced fission generates extra neutrons which can induce further fissions in the next generation and so on in a chain reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] The chain reaction is characterized by the *neutron multiplication factor k*, which is defined as the ratio of the number of neutrons in one generation to the number in the preceding generation.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] If, in a reactor, *k* is less than unity, the reactor is subcritical, the number of neutrons decreases and the chain reaction dies out.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] If *k* > 1, the reactor is supercritical and the chain reaction diverges.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] This is the situation in a fission bomb where growth is at an explosive rate.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] If *k* is exactly unity, the reactions proceed at a steady rate and the reactor is said to be critical.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] It is possible to achieve criticality in a reactor using natural uranium as fuel, provided that the neutrons have been efficiently moderated to thermal energies." Moderators include light water, heavy water, and graphite.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Lee, "For all nuclear reactors in operation and those under development, the nuclear fuel cycle is based on one of three *fissile* materials, 235U, 233U, and 239Pu, and the associated isotopic chains.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Lee states, "One important comparison for the three major fissile nuclides, 235U, 233U, and 239Pu, is their breeding potential.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] A *breeder* is by definition a reactor that produces more fissile material than it consumes and needs a minimum of two neutrons produced for each neutron absorbed in a fissile nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Critical fission reactors are the most common type of nuclear reactor.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] In a critical fission reactor, neutrons produced by fission of fuel atoms are used to induce yet more fissions, to sustain a controllable amount of energy release.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Devices that produce engineered but non-self-sustaining fission reactions are subcritical fission reactors.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Such devices use radioactive decay or particle accelerators to trigger fissions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] While, in principle, all fission reactors can act in all three capacities, in practice the tasks lead to conflicting engineering goals and most reactors have been built with only one of the above tasks in mind.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] (There are several early counter-examples, such as the Hanford N reactor, now decommissioned).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] As of 2019, the 448 nuclear power plants worldwide provided a capacity of 398 GWE, with about 85% being light-water cooled reactors such as pressurized water reactors or boiling water reactors.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p01] Energy from fission is transmitted through conduction or convection to the nuclear reactor coolant, then to a heat exchanger, and the resultant generated steam is used to drive a turbine or generator.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In 1911, Ernest Rutherford proposed a model of the atom in which a very small, dense and positively charged nucleus of protons was surrounded by orbiting, negatively charged electrons (the Rutherford model).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Niels Bohr improved upon this in 1913 by reconciling the quantum behavior of electrons (the Bohr model).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In 1928, George Gamow proposed the liquid-drop model, which became essential to understanding the physics of fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In 1896, Henri Becquerel had found, and Marie Curie named, radioactivity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In 1919, following up on an earlier anomaly Ernest Marsden noted in 1915, Rutherford attempted to "break up the atom." Rutherford was able to accomplish the first artificial transmutation of nitrogen into oxygen, using alpha particles directed at nitrogen 14N + α → 17O + p.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Rutherford stated, "...we must conclude that the nitrogen atom is disintegrated," while the newspapers stated he had *split the atom*.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] This was the first observation of a nuclear reaction, that is, a reaction in which particles from one decay are used to transform another atomic nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] It also offered a new way to study the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Rutherford and James Chadwick then used alpha particles to "disintegrate" boron, fluorine, sodium, aluminum, and phosphorus before reaching a limitation associated with the energy of his alpha particle source.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Eventually, in 1932, a fully artificial nuclear reaction and nuclear transmutation was achieved by Rutherford's colleagues Ernest Walton and John Cockcroft, who used artificially accelerated protons against lithium-7, to split this nucleus into two alpha particles.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The feat was popularly known as "splitting the atom", and would win them the 1951 Nobel Prize in Physics for *"Transmutation of atomic nuclei by artificially accelerated atomic particles"*, although it was not the nuclear fission reaction later discovered in heavy elements.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] English physicist James Chadwick discovered the neutron in 1932.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Chadwick used an ionization chamber to observe protons knocked out of several elements by beryllium radiation, following up on earlier observations made by Joliot-Curies.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] And the answer was a neutral particle." Subsequently, he communicated his findings in more detail.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In the process, they discovered the ability of hydrogen to slow down the neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Enrico Fermi and his colleagues in Rome studied the results of bombarding uranium with neutrons in 1934.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Fermi concluded that his experiments had created new elements with 93 and 94 protons, which the group dubbed ausenium and hesperium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Although Noddack was a renowned analytical chemist, she lacked the background in physics to appreciate the enormity of what she was proposing.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] After the Fermi publication, Otto Hahn, Lise Meitner, and Fritz Strassmann began performing similar experiments in Berlin.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Meitner, an Austrian Jew, lost her Austrian citizenship with the *Anschluss*, the union of Austria with Germany in March 1938, but she fled in July 1938 to Sweden and started a correspondence by mail with Hahn in Berlin.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] By coincidence, her nephew Otto Robert Frisch, also a refugee, was also in Sweden when Meitner received a letter from Hahn dated 19 December describing his chemical proof that some of the product of the bombardment of uranium with neutrons was barium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Hahn suggested a *bursting* of the nucleus, but he was unsure of what the physical basis for the results were.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Barium had an atomic mass 40% less than uranium, and no previously known methods of radioactive decay could account for such a large difference in the mass of the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Frisch was skeptical, but Meitner trusted Hahn's ability as a chemist.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Marie Curie had been separating barium from radium for many years, and the techniques were well known.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Meitner and Frisch then correctly interpreted Hahn's results to mean that the nucleus of uranium had split roughly in half.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Frisch suggested the process be named "nuclear fission", by analogy to the process of living cell division into two cells, which was then called binary fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Just as the term nuclear "chain reaction" would later be borrowed from chemistry, so the term "fission" was borrowed from biology.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] News spread quickly of the new discovery, which was correctly seen as an entirely novel physical effect with great scientific—and potentially practical—possibilities.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Meitner's and Frisch's interpretation of the discovery of Hahn and Strassmann crossed the Atlantic Ocean with Niels Bohr, who was to lecture at Princeton University.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Rabi and Willis Lamb, two Columbia University physicists working at Princeton, heard the news and carried it back to Columbia.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Rabi said he told Enrico Fermi; Fermi gave credit to Lamb.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Bohr soon thereafter went from Princeton to Columbia to see Fermi.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Not finding Fermi in his office, Bohr went down to the cyclotron area and found Herbert L.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] It was clear to a number of scientists at Columbia that they should try to detect the energy released in the nuclear fission of uranium from neutron bombardment.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 25 January 1939, a Columbia University team conducted the first nuclear fission experiment in the United States, which was done in the basement of Pupin Hall.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The experiment involved placing uranium oxide inside of an ionization chamber and irradiating it with neutrons, and measuring the energy thus released.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The results confirmed that fission was occurring and hinted strongly that it was the isotope uranium 235 in particular that was fissioning.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The next day, the fifth Washington Conference on Theoretical Physics began in Washington, D.C. under the joint auspices of the George Washington University and the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] There, the news on nuclear fission was spread even further, which fostered many more experimental demonstrations.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The 6 January 1939 Hahn and Strassman paper announced the discover of fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The 11 February 1939 paper by Meitner and Frisch compared the process to the division of a liquid drop and estimated the energy released at 200 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The 1 September 1939 paper by Bohr and Wheeler used this liquid drop model to quantify fission details, including the energy released, estimated the cross section for neutron-induced fission, and deduced 235 U was the major contributor to that cross section and slow-neutron fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] During this period the Hungarian physicist Leó Szilárd realized that the neutron-driven fission of heavy atoms could be used to create a nuclear chain reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Such a reaction using neutrons was an idea he had first formulated in 1933, upon reading Rutherford's disparaging remarks about generating power from neutron collisions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] However, Szilárd had not been able to achieve a neutron-driven chain reaction using beryllium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Szilard now urged Fermi (in New York) and Frédéric Joliot-Curie (in Paris) to refrain from publishing on the possibility of a chain reaction, lest the Nazi government become aware of the possibilities on the eve of what would later be known as World War II.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] With some hesitation Fermi agreed to self-censor.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] But Joliot-Curie did not, and in April 1939 his team in Paris, including Hans von Halban and Lew Kowarski, reported in the journal *Nature* that the number of neutrons emitted with nuclear fission of uranium was then reported at 3.5 per fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] With the news of fission neutrons from uranium fission, Szilárd immediately understood the possibility of a nuclear chain reaction using uranium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In the summer, Fermi and Szilard proposed the idea of a nuclear reactor (pile) to mediate this process.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The pile would use natural uranium as fuel.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Fermi had shown much earlier that neutrons were far more effectively captured by atoms if they were of low energy (so-called "slow" or "thermal" neutrons), because for quantum reasons it made the atoms look like much larger targets to the neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Thus to slow down the secondary neutrons released by the fissioning uranium nuclei, Fermi and Szilard proposed a graphite "moderator", against which the fast, high-energy secondary neutrons would collide, effectively slowing them down.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] With enough uranium, and with sufficiently pure graphite, their "pile" could theoretically sustain a slow-neutron chain reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] This would result in the production of heat, as well as the creation of radioactive fission products.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In August 1939, Szilard, Teller and Wigner thought that the Germans might make use of the fission chain reaction and were spurred to attempt to attract the attention of the United States government to the issue.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Towards this, they persuaded Albert Einstein to lend his name to a letter directed to President Franklin Roosevelt.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 11 October, the Einstein–Szilárd letter was delivered via Alexander Sachs.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Roosevelt quickly understood the implications, stating, "Alex, what you are after is to see that the Nazis don't blow us up." Roosevelt ordered the formation of the Advisory Committee on Uranium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In February 1940, encouraged by Fermi and John R.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Nier was able to separate U-235 and U-238 from uranium tetrachloride in a glass mass spectrometer.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] At the University of Birmingham, Frisch teamed up with Rudolf Peierls, who had been working on a critical mass formula. assuming isotope separation was possible, they considered 235U, which had a cross section not yet determined, but which was assumed to be much larger than that of natural uranium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] They calculated only a pound or two in a volume less than a golf ball, would result in a chain reaction faster than vaporization, and the resultant explosion would generate temperature greater than the interior of the sun, and pressures greater than the center of the earth.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 10 April 1940, the first meeting of the MAUD Committee was held.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In December 1940, Franz Simon at Oxford wrote his Estimate of the size of an actual separation plant." Simon proposed gaseous diffusion as the best method for uranium isotope separation.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 28 March 1941, Emilio Segré and Glen Seaborg reported on the "strong indications that 239Pu undergoes fission with slow neutrons." This meant chemical separation was an alternative to uranium isotope separation.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Instead, a nuclear reactor fueled with ordinary uranium could produce a plutonium isotope as a nuclear explosive substitute for 235U.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In May, they demonstrated the cross section of plutonium was 1.7 times that of U235.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] When plutonium's cross section for fast fission was measured to be ten times that of U238, plutonium became a viable option for a bomb.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In October 1941, MAUD released its final report to the U.S.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In November 1941, John Dunning and Eugene T.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Booth were able to demonstrate the enrichment of uranium through gaseous barrier diffusion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 27 November, Bush delivered to third National Academy of Sciences report to Roosevelt.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The report, amongst other things, called for parallel development of all isotope-separation systems.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 6 December, Bush and Conant reorganized the Uranium Committee's tasks, with Harold Urey developing gaseous diffusion, Lawrence developing electromagnetic separation, Eger V.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Murphree developing centrifuges, and Arthur Compton responsible for theoretical studies and design.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 23 April 1942, Met Lab scientists discussed seven possible ways to extract plutonium from irradiated uranium, and decided to pursue investigation of all seven.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 17 June, the first batch of uranium nitrate hexahydrate (UNH) was undergoing neutron bombardment in the Washington University in St.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 27 July, the irradiated UNH was ready for Glenn T.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] On 20 August, using ultramicrochemistry techniques, they successfully extracted plutonium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In May 1942, Gertrude Scharff Goldhaber at Brookhaven National Laboratory reports for the first the emission of multiple neutrons during spontaneous fission of uranium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In April 1939, creating a chain reaction in natural uranium became the goal of Fermi and Szilard, as opposed to isotope separation.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Their first efforts involved five hundred pounds of uranium oxide from the Eldorado Radium Corporation.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Packed into fifty-two cans two inches in diameter and two feet long in a tank of manganese solution, they were able to confirm more neutrons were emitted than absorbed.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] However, the hydrogen within the water absorbed the slow neutrons necessary for fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Carbon in the form of graphite, was then considered, because of its smaller capture cross section.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In April 1940, Fermi was able to confirm carbon's potential for a slow-neutron chain reaction, after receiving National Carbon Company's graphite bricks at their Pupin Laboratories.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In August and September, the Columbia team enlarged upon the cross section measurements by making a series of exponential "piles".
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The first piles consisted of a uranium-graphite lattice, consisting of 288 cans, each containing 60 pounds of uranium oxide, surrounded by graphite bricks.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Fermi's goal was to determine critical mass necessary to sustain neutron generation.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Fermi defined the reproduction factor k for assessing the chain reaction, with a value of 1.0 denoting a sustained chain reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In September 1941, Fermi's team was only able to achieve a k value of 0.87.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In April 1942, before the project was centralized in Chicago, they had achieved 0.918 by removing moisture from the oxide.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In May 1942, Fermi planned a full-scale chain reacting pile, Chicago Pile-1, after one of the exponential piles at Stagg Field reached a k of 0.995.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Between 15 September and 15 November, Herbert L.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Anderson and Walter Zinn built sixteen exponential piles.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Acquisition of purer forms of graphite, without traces of boron and its large cross section, became paramount.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Also important was the acquisition of highly purified forms of oxide from Mallinckrodt Chemical Works.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Finally, acquiring pure uranium metal from the Ames process, meant the replacement of oxide pseudospheres with Frank Spedding's "eggs".
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Starting on 16 November 1942, Fermi had Anderson and Zinn working in two twelve-hours shifts, constructing a pile that eventually reached 57 layers by 1 Dec.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The final pile consisted of 771,000 pounds of graphite, 80,590 pounds of uranium oxide, and 12,400 pounds of uranium metal, with ten cadmium control rods.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Neutron intensity was measured with a boron trifluoride counter, with the control rods removed, after the end of each shift.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] 1942, with k approaching 1.0, Fermi had all but one of the control rod removed, and gradually removed the last one.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The neutron counter clicks increased, as did the pen recorder, when Fermi announced "The pile has gone critical." They had achieved a k of 1.006, which meant neutron intensity doubled every two minutes, in addition to breeding plutonium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In the United States, an all-out effort for making atomic weapons was begun in late 1942.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Army Corps of Engineers in 1943, and known as the Manhattan Engineer District.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] The top-secret Manhattan Project, as it was colloquially known, was led by General Leslie R.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Other sites, notably the Berkeley Radiation Laboratory and the Metallurgical Laboratory at the University of Chicago, played important contributing roles.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Overall scientific direction of the project was managed by the physicist J.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In July 1945, the first atomic explosive device, dubbed "The Gadget", was detonated in the New Mexico desert in the Trinity test.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] It was fueled by plutonium created at Hanford.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] In August 1945, two more atomic devices – "Little Boy", a uranium-235 bomb, and "Fat Man", a plutonium bomb – were used against the Japanese cities of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] At three ore deposits at Oklo in Gabon, sixteen sites (the so-called Oklo Fossil Reactors) have been discovered at which self-sustaining nuclear fission took place approximately 2 billion years ago.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] French physicist Francis Perrin discovered the Oklo Fossil Reactors in 1972, but it was postulated by Paul Kuroda in 1956.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fission-p02] Large-scale natural uranium fission chain reactions, moderated by normal water, had occurred far in the past and would not be possible now.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Fusion processes require an extremely large triple product of temperature, density, and confinement time.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] These conditions occur only in stellar cores, advanced nuclear weapons, and are approached in fusion power experiments.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] A nuclear fusion process that produces atomic nuclei lighter than nickel-62 is generally exothermic, due to the positive gradient of the nuclear binding energy curve.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The most fusible nuclei are among the lightest, especially deuterium, tritium, and helium-3.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The opposite process, nuclear fission, is most energetic for very heavy nuclei, especially the actinides.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Applications of fusion include fusion power, thermonuclear weapons, boosted fission weapons, neutron sources, and superheavy element production.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] American chemist William Draper Harkins was the first to propose the concept of nuclear fusion in 1915.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Francis William Aston's 1919 invention of the mass spectrometer allowed the discovery that four hydrogen atoms are heavier than one helium atom.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Thus in 1920, Arthur Eddington correctly predicted fusion of hydrogen into helium could be the primary source of stellar energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Quantum tunneling was discovered by Friedrich Hund in 1927, with relation to electron levels.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In 1928, George Gamow was the first to apply tunneling to the nucleus, first to alpha decay, then to fusion as an inverse process.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] From this, in 1929, Robert Atkinson and Fritz Houtermans made the first estimates for stellar fusion rates.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In 1938, Hans Bethe worked with Charles Critchfield to enumerate the proton–proton chain that dominates Sun-type stars.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In 1939, Bethe published the discovery of the CNO cycle common to higher-mass stars.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] During the 1920s, Patrick Blackett made the first conclusive experiments in artificial nuclear transmutation at the Cavendish Laboratory.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] There, John Cockcroft and Ernest Walton built their generator on the inspiration of Gamow's paper.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] where the intermediary nuclide was later confirmed to be the extremely short-lived beryllium-8.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This has a claim to the first artificial fusion reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The Radiation Lab, only detecting the resulting energized protons and neutrons, misinterpreted the source as an exothermic disintegration of the deuterons, now known to be impossible.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In May 1934, Mark Oliphant, Paul Harteck, and Ernest Rutherford at the Cavendish Laboratory, published an intentional deuterium fusion experiment, and made the discovery of both tritium and helium-3.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This is widely considered the first experimental demonstration of fusion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Research into fusion for military purposes began in the early 1940s as part of the Manhattan Project.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In 1941, Enrico Fermi and Edward Teller had a conversation about the possibility of a fission bomb creating conditions for thermonuclear fusion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In 1942, Emil Konopinski brought Ruhlig's work on the deuterium–tritium reaction to the project's attention.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Robert Oppenheimer initially commissioned physicists at Chicago and Cornell to use the Harvard University cyclotron to secretly investigate its cross-section, and that of the lithium reaction (see below).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Measurements were obtained at Purdue, Chicago, and Los Alamos from 1942 to 1946.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Theoretical assumptions about DT fusion gave it a similar cross-section to DD.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] However, in 1946 Egon Bretscher discovered a resonance enhancement giving the DT reaction a cross-section ~100 times larger.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] From 1945, John von Neumann, Teller, and other Los Alamos scientists used ENIAC, one of the first electronic computers, to simulate thermonuclear weapon detonations.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The first artificial thermonuclear fusion reaction occurred during the 1951 US Greenhouse George nuclear test, using a small amount of deuterium–tritium gas.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This produced the largest yield to date, at 225 kt, 15 times that of Little Boy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The first "true" thermonuclear weapon detonation i.e. a two-stage device, was the 1952 Ivy Mike test of a liquid deuterium-fusing device, yielding over 10 Mt.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The key to this jump was the full utilization of the fission blast by the Teller–Ulam design.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The Soviet Union had begun their focus on a hydrogen bomb program earlier, and in 1953 carried out the RDS-6s test.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This had international impacts as the first air-deliverable bomb using fusion, but yielded 400 kt and was limited by its single-stage design.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The first Soviet two-stage test was RDS-37 in 1955 yielding 1.5 Mt, using an independently reached version of the Teller–Ulam design.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Modern devices benefit from the usage of solid lithium deuteride with an enrichment of lithium-6.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] During thermonuclear detonations, this provides tritium for the highly energetic DT reaction, and benefits from its neutron production, creating a closed neutron cycle.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] While fusion bomb detonations were loosely considered for energy production, the possibility of controlled and sustained reactions remained the scientific focus for peaceful fusion power.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Research into developing controlled fusion inside fusion reactors has been ongoing since the 1930s, with Los Alamos National Laboratory's Scylla I device producing the first laboratory thermonuclear fusion in 1958, but the technology is still in its developmental phase.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The first experiments producing large amounts of controlled fusion power were the experiments with mixes of deuterium and tritium in Tokamaks.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Experiments in the TFTR at the PPPL in Princeton University Princeton NJ, USA during 1993–1996 produced 1.6 GJ of fusion energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The peak fusion power was 10.3 MW from 3.7×1018 reactions per second, and peak fusion energy created in one discharge was 7.6 MJ.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Subsequent experiments in the JET in 1997 achieved a peak fusion power of 16 MW (5.8×1018/s).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The central *Q*, defined as the local fusion power produced to the local applied heating power, is computed to be 1.3.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] A JET experiment in 2024 produced 69 MJ of fusion power, consuming 0.2 mgm of D and T.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The US National Ignition Facility, which uses laser-driven inertial confinement fusion, was designed with a goal of achieving a fusion energy gain factor (Q) of larger than one; the first large-scale laser target experiments were performed in June 2009 and ignition experiments began in early 2011.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] On 13 December 2022, the United States Department of Energy announced that on 5 December 2022, they had successfully accomplished break-even fusion, "delivering 2.05 megajoules (MJ) of energy to the target, resulting in 3.15 MJ of fusion energy output".
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The rate of supplying power to the experimental test cell is hundreds of times larger than the power delivered to the target.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Prior to this breakthrough, controlled fusion reactions had been unable to produce break-even (self-sustaining) controlled fusion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The two most advanced approaches for it are magnetic confinement (toroid designs) and inertial confinement (laser designs).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Workable designs for a toroidal reactor that theoretically will deliver ten times more fusion energy than the amount needed to heat plasma to the required temperatures are in development (see ITER).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The ITER facility is currently expected to initiate plasma experiments in 2034, but is not expected to begin full deuterium–tritium fusion until 2039.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Private companies pursuing the commercialization of nuclear fusion received $2.6 billion in private funding in 2021 alone, going to many notable startups including but not limited to Commonwealth Fusion Systems, Helion Energy Inc., General Fusion, TAE Technologies Inc. and Zap Energy Inc.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] One of the most recent breakthroughs to date in maintaining a sustained fusion reaction occurred in France's WEST fusion reactor.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] It maintained a 90 million degree plasma for a record time of six minutes.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This is a tokamak-style reactor which is the same style as the upcoming ITER reactor.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Lighter nuclei (nuclei smaller than iron and nickel) are sufficiently small and proton-poor to allow the nuclear force to overcome the Coulomb force.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This is because the nucleus is sufficiently small that all nucleons feel the short-range attractive force at least as strongly as they feel the infinite-range Coulomb repulsion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Building up nuclei from lighter nuclei by fusion releases the extra energy from the net attraction of particles.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] For larger nuclei, however, no energy is released, because the nuclear force is short-range and cannot act across larger nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Fusion powers stars and produces most elements lighter than cobalt in a process called nucleosynthesis.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The Sun is a main-sequence star, and, as such, generates its energy by nuclear fusion of hydrogen nuclei into helium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In its core, the Sun fuses 620 million metric tons of hydrogen and makes 616 million metric tons of helium each second.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The fusion of lighter elements in stars releases energy and the mass that always accompanies it.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] For example, in the fusion of two hydrogen nuclei to form helium, 0.645% of the mass is carried away in the form of kinetic energy of an alpha particle or other forms of energy, such as electromagnetic radiation.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] It takes considerable energy to force nuclei to fuse, even those of the lightest element, hydrogen.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] When accelerated to high enough speeds, nuclei can overcome this electrostatic repulsion and be brought close enough such that the attractive nuclear force is greater than the repulsive Coulomb force.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The strong force grows rapidly once the nuclei are close enough, and the fusing nucleons can essentially "fall" into each other and the result is fusion; this is an exothermic process.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Energy released in most nuclear reactions is much larger than in chemical reactions, because the binding energy that holds a nucleus together is greater than the energy that holds electrons to a nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] For example, the ionization energy gained by adding an electron to a hydrogen nucleus is 13.6 eV—less than one-millionth of the 17.6 MeV released in the deuterium–tritium (D–T) reaction shown in the adjacent diagram.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Via the mass–energy equivalence, fusion yields a 0.7% efficiency of reactant mass into energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This can only be exceeded by the extreme cases of the accretion process involving neutron stars or black holes, approaching 40% efficiency, and antimatter annihilation at 100% efficiency.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Fusion is responsible for the astrophysical production of the majority of elements lighter than iron.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This includes most types of Big Bang nucleosynthesis and stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Non-fusion processes that contribute include the s-process and r-process in neutron merger and supernova nucleosynthesis, responsible for elements heavier than iron.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] An important fusion process is the stellar nucleosynthesis that powers stars, including the Sun.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In the 20th century, it was recognized that the energy released from nuclear fusion reactions accounts for the longevity of stellar heat and light.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The fusion of nuclei in a star, starting from its initial hydrogen and helium abundance, provides that energy and synthesizes new nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Different reaction chains are involved, depending on the mass of the star (and therefore the pressure and temperature in its core).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Around 1920, Arthur Eddington anticipated the discovery and mechanism of nuclear fusion processes in stars, in his paper *The Internal Constitution of the Stars*.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] At that time, the source of stellar energy was unknown; Eddington correctly speculated that the source was fusion of hydrogen into helium, liberating enormous energy according to Einstein's equation *E* = *mc*2.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This was a particularly remarkable development since at that time fusion and thermonuclear energy had not yet been discovered, nor even that stars are largely composed of hydrogen .
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The only other known plausible source of energy was conversion of matter to energy; Einstein had shown some years earlier that a small amount of matter was equivalent to a large amount of energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This suggested that if such a combination could happen, it would release considerable energy as a byproduct.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] If a star contained just 5% of fusible hydrogen, it would suffice to explain how stars got their energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Further elements might also be fused, and other scientists had speculated that stars were the "crucible" in which light elements combined to create heavy elements, but without more accurate measurements of their atomic masses nothing more could be said at the time.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] All of these speculations were proven correct in the following decades.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The primary source of solar energy, and that of similar size stars, is the fusion of hydrogen to form helium (the proton–proton chain reaction), which occurs at a solar-core temperature of 14 million kelvin.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The net result is the fusion of four protons into one alpha particle, with the release of two positrons and two neutrinos (which changes two of the protons into neutrons), and energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In heavier stars, the CNO cycle and other processes are more important.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] As a star uses up a substantial fraction of its hydrogen, it begins to fuse heavier elements.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In massive cores, silicon-burning is the final fusion cycle, leading to a build-up of iron and nickel nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Nuclear binding energy makes the production of elements heavier than nickel via fusion energetically unfavorable.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] These elements are produced in non-fusion processes: the s-process, r-process, and the variety of processes that can produce p-nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Such processes occur in giant star shells, or supernovae, or neutron star mergers.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Brown dwarfs fuse deuterium and in very high mass cases also fuse lithium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Carbon–oxygen white dwarfs, which accrete matter either from an active stellar companion or white dwarf merger, approach the Chandrasekhar limit of 1.44 solar masses.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Immediately prior, carbon burning fusion begins, destroying the Earth-sized dwarf within one second, in a Type Ia supernova.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Much more rarely, helium white dwarfs may merge, which does not cause an explosion but begins helium burning in an extreme type of helium star.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Some neutron stars accrete hydrogen and helium from an active stellar companion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Periodically, the helium accretion reaches a critical level, and a thermonuclear burn wave propagates across the surface, on the timescale of one second.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Similar to stellar fusion, extreme conditions within black hole accretion disks can allow fusion reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Calculations show the most energetic reactions occur around lower stellar mass black holes, below 10 solar masses, compared to those above 100.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Beyond five Schwarzschild radii, carbon-burning and fusion of helium-3 dominates the reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Within this distance, around lower mass black holes, fusion of nitrogen, oxygen, neon, and magnesium can occur.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In the extreme limit, the silicon-burning process can begin with the fusion of silicon and selenium nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] From the period approximately 10 seconds to 20 minutes after the Big Bang, the universe cooled from over 100 keV to 1 keV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This allowed the combination of protons and neutrons in deuterium nuclei, and beginning a rapid fusion chain into tritium and helium-3 and ending in predominantly helium-4, with a minimal fraction of lithium, beryllium, and boron nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Observational evidence shows that pockets of gas in the early universe became thick enough to collapse under their own gravity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This activated nuclear fusion with the formation of the first stars around 13.6 billion years ago.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] A substantial energy barrier of electrostatic forces must be overcome before fusion can occur.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] At large distances, two naked nuclei repel one another because of the repulsive electrostatic force between their positively charged protons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] If two nuclei can be brought close enough together, however, the electrostatic repulsion can be overcome by the quantum effect in which nuclei can tunnel through coulomb forces.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] When a nucleon such as a proton or neutron is added to a nucleus, the nuclear force attracts it to all the other nucleons of the nucleus (if the atom is small enough), but primarily to its immediate neighbors due to the short range of the force.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The nucleons in the interior of a nucleus have more neighboring nucleons than those on the surface.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Since smaller nuclei have a larger surface-area-to-volume ratio, the binding energy per nucleon due to the nuclear force generally increases with the size of the nucleus but approaches a limiting value corresponding to that of a nucleus with a diameter of about four nucleons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] It is important to keep in mind that nucleons are quantum objects.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The electrostatic force, on the other hand, is an inverse-square force, so a proton added to a nucleus will feel an electrostatic repulsion from *all* the other protons in the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The electrostatic energy per nucleon due to the electrostatic force thus increases without limit as nuclei atomic number grows.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The net result of the opposing electrostatic and strong nuclear forces is that the binding energy per nucleon generally increases with increasing size, up to the elements iron and nickel, and then decreases for heavier nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Eventually, the binding energy becomes negative and very heavy nuclei (all with more than 208 nucleons, corresponding to a diameter of about 6 nucleons) are not stable.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The four most tightly bound nuclei, in decreasing order of binding energy per nucleon, are 62 Ni, 58 Fe, 56 Fe, and 60 Ni.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Even though the nickel isotope, 62 Ni, is more stable, the iron isotope 56 Fe is an order of magnitude more common.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This is due to the fact that there is no easy way for stars to create 62 Ni through the alpha process.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] An exception to this general trend is the helium-4 nucleus, whose binding energy is higher than that of lithium, the next heavier element.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This is because protons and neutrons are fermions, which according to the Pauli exclusion principle cannot exist in the same nucleus in exactly the same state.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Each proton or neutron's energy state in a nucleus can accommodate both a spin up particle and a spin down particle.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Helium-4 has an anomalously large binding energy because its nucleus consists of two protons and two neutrons (it is a doubly magic nucleus), so all four of its nucleons can be in the ground state.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Any additional nucleons would have to go into higher energy states.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Indeed, the helium-4 nucleus is so tightly bound that it is commonly treated as a single quantum mechanical particle in nuclear physics, namely, the alpha particle.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The situation is similar if two nuclei are brought together.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] As they approach each other, all the protons in one nucleus repel all the protons in the other.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Not until the two nuclei actually come close enough for long enough so the strong attractive nuclear force can take over and overcome the repulsive electrostatic force.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This can also be described as the nuclei overcoming the so-called Coulomb barrier.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The kinetic energy to achieve this can be lower than the barrier itself because of quantum tunneling.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The Coulomb barrier is smallest for isotopes of hydrogen, as their nuclei contain only a single positive charge.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] A diproton is not stable, so neutrons must also be involved, ideally in such a way that a helium nucleus, with its extremely tight binding, is one of the products.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Using deuterium–tritium fuel, the resulting energy barrier is about 0.1 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In comparison, the energy needed to remove an electron from hydrogen is 13.6 eV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The (intermediate) result of the fusion is an unstable 5He nucleus, which immediately ejects a neutron with 14.1 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The recoil energy of the remaining 4He nucleus is 3.5 MeV, so the total energy liberated is 17.6 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This is many times more than what was needed to overcome the energy barrier.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The reaction cross section (σ) is a measure of the probability of a fusion reaction as a function of the relative velocity of the two reactant nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] If the reactants have a distribution of velocities, e.g. a thermal distribution, then it is useful to perform an average over the distributions of the product of cross-section and velocity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This average is called the 'reactivity', denoted ⟨*σv*⟩.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] If a species of nuclei is reacting with a nucleus like itself, such as the DD reaction, then the product $n_{1}n_{2}$ must be replaced by $n^{2}/2$ .
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] $\langle \sigma v\rangle$ increases from virtually zero at room temperatures up to meaningful magnitudes at temperatures of 10–100 keV/kB.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] At these temperatures, well above typical ionization energies (13.6 eV in the hydrogen case), the fusion reactants exist in a plasma state.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The significance of $\langle \sigma v\rangle$ as a function of temperature in a device with a particular energy confinement time is found by considering the Lawson criterion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This is an extremely challenging barrier to overcome on Earth, which explains why fusion research has taken many years to reach the current advanced technical state.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Thermonuclear fusion is the process of atomic nuclei combining or "fusing" using high temperatures to drive them close enough together for this to become possible.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Such temperatures cause the matter to become a plasma and, if confined, fusion reactions may occur due to collisions with extreme thermal kinetic energies of the particles.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Temperature is a measure of the average kinetic energy of particles, so by heating the material it will gain energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] After reaching sufficient temperature, given by the Lawson criterion, the energy of accidental collisions within the plasma is high enough to overcome the Coulomb barrier and the particles may fuse together.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In a deuterium–tritium fusion reaction, for example, the energy necessary to overcome the Coulomb barrier is 0.1 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Converting between energy and temperature shows that the 0.1 MeV barrier would be overcome at a temperature in excess of 1.2 billion kelvin.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] There are two effects that are needed to lower the actual temperature.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] One is the fact that temperature is the *average* kinetic energy, implying that some nuclei at this temperature would actually have much higher energy than 0.1 MeV, while others would be much lower.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] It is the nuclei in the high-energy tail of the velocity distribution that account for most of the fusion reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The nuclei do not actually have to have enough energy to overcome the Coulomb barrier completely.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] If they have nearly enough energy, they can tunnel through the remaining barrier.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] For these reasons fuel at lower temperatures will still undergo fusion events, at a lower rate.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Accelerator-based light-ion fusion is a technique using particle accelerators to achieve particle kinetic energies sufficient to induce light-ion fusion reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Accelerating light ions is relatively easy, and can be done in an efficient manner—requiring only a vacuum tube, a pair of electrodes, and a high-voltage transformer; fusion can be observed with as little as 10 kV between the electrodes.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The system can be arranged to accelerate ions into a static fuel-infused target, known as *beam–target* fusion, or by accelerating two streams of ions towards each other, *beam–beam* fusion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The key problem with accelerator-based fusion (and with cold targets in general) is that fusion cross sections are many orders of magnitude lower than Coulomb interaction cross-sections.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Therefore, the vast majority of ions expend their energy emitting bremsstrahlung radiation and the ionization of atoms of the target.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Devices referred to as sealed-tube neutron generators are particularly relevant to this discussion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] These small devices are miniature particle accelerators filled with deuterium and tritium gas in an arrangement that allows ions of those nuclei to be accelerated against hydride targets, also containing deuterium and tritium, where fusion takes place, releasing a flux of neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Hundreds of neutron generators are produced annually for use in the petroleum industry where they are used in measurement equipment for locating and mapping oil reserves.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] A number of attempts to recirculate the ions that "miss" collisions have been made over the years.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] One of the better-known attempts in the 1970s was Migma, which used a unique particle storage ring to capture ions into circular orbits and return them to the reaction area.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Theoretical calculations made during funding reviews pointed out that the system would have significant difficulty scaling up to contain enough fusion fuel to be relevant as a power source.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In the 1990s, a new arrangement using a field-reversed configuration (FRC) as the storage system was proposed by Norman Rostoker and continues to be studied by TAE Technologies as of 2021.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] A closely related approach is to merge two FRC's rotating in opposite directions, which is being actively studied by Helion Energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Because these approaches all have ion energies well beyond the Coulomb barrier, they often suggest the use of alternative fuel cycles like p-11B that are too difficult to attempt using conventional approaches.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Fusion of very heavy target nuclei with accelerated ion beams is the primary method of element synthesis.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Muon-catalyzed fusion is a fusion process that occurs at ordinary temperatures.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] It was studied in detail by Steven Jones in the early 1980s.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Net energy production from this reaction has been unsuccessful because of the high energy required to create muons, their short 2.2 μs half-life, and the high chance that a muon will bind to the new alpha particle and thus stop catalyzing fusion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Some other confinement principles have been investigated.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The key problem in achieving thermonuclear fusion is how to confine the hot plasma.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Due to the high temperature, the plasma cannot be in direct contact with any solid material, so it has to be located in a vacuum.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Also, high temperatures imply high pressures.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The plasma tends to expand immediately and some force is necessary to act against it.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This force can take one of three forms: gravitation in stars, magnetic forces in magnetic confinement fusion reactors, or inertial as the fusion reaction may occur before the plasma starts to expand, so the plasma's inertia is keeping the material together.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] One force capable of confining the fuel well enough to satisfy the Lawson criterion is gravity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The mass needed, however, is so great that gravitational confinement is only found in stars—the least massive stars capable of sustained fusion are red dwarfs, while brown dwarfs are able to fuse deuterium and lithium if they are of sufficient mass.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In stars heavy enough, after the supply of hydrogen is exhausted in their cores, their cores (or a shell around the core) start fusing helium to carbon.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] In the most massive stars (at least 8–11 solar masses), the process is continued until some of their energy is produced by fusing lighter elements to iron.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] As iron has one of the highest binding energies, reactions producing heavier elements are generally endothermic.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Therefore, significant amounts of heavier elements are not formed during stable periods of massive star evolution, but are formed in supernova explosions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Some lighter stars also form these elements in the outer parts of the stars over long periods of time, by absorbing energy from fusion in the inside of the star, by absorbing neutrons that are emitted from the fusion process.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] All of the elements heavier than iron have some potential energy to release, in theory.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] At the extremely heavy end of element production, these heavier elements can produce energy in the process of being split again back toward the size of iron, in the process of nuclear fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Nuclear fission thus releases energy that has been stored, sometimes billions of years before, during stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Electrically charged particles (such as fuel ions) will follow magnetic field lines (see Guiding centre).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The fusion fuel can therefore be trapped using a strong magnetic field.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] A variety of magnetic configurations exist, including the toroidal geometries of tokamaks and stellarators and open-ended mirror confinement systems.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] A third confinement principle is to apply a rapid pulse of energy to a large part of the surface of a pellet of fusion fuel, causing it to simultaneously "implode" and heat to very high pressure and temperature.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] If the fuel is dense enough and hot enough, the fusion reaction rate will be high enough to burn a significant fraction of the fuel before it has dissipated.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] To achieve these extreme conditions, the initially cold fuel must be explosively compressed.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Inertial confinement is used in the hydrogen bomb, where the driver is x-rays created by a fission bomb.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Inertial confinement is also attempted in "controlled" nuclear fusion, where the driver is a laser, ion, or electron beam, or a Z-pinch.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Another method is to use conventional high explosive material to compress a fuel to fusion conditions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The UTIAS explosive-driven-implosion facility was used to produce stable, centred and focused hemispherical implosions to generate neutrons from D–D reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The simplest and most direct method proved to be in a predetonated stoichiometric mixture of deuterium–oxygen.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The other successful method was using a miniature Voitenko compressor, where a plane diaphragm was driven by the implosion wave into a secondary small spherical cavity that contained pure deuterium gas at one atmosphere.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] There are also inertial electrostatic confinement fusion devices, which confine ions via electrostatic fields.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] This device has a cathode inside an anode wire cage.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Positive ions fly toward the negative inner cage, and are heated by the electric field in the process.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] If they miss the inner cage they can collide and fuse.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] However, most ions hit the cathode, creating prohibitory high conduction losses.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Also, fusion rates in fusors are very low due to competing physical effects, such as energy loss in the form of light radiation.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Designs have been proposed to avoid the problems associated with the cage, by generating the field using a non-neutral cloud.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] These include a plasma oscillating device, a Penning trap and the polywell.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] The technology is relatively immature, and many scientific and engineering questions remain.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Starting in 1999, many amateurs have built homemade fusion reactors using fusors.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p01] Other IEC devices include: the Polywell, MIX POPS and Marble concepts.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] At the temperatures and densities in stellar cores, the rates of fusion reactions are notoriously slow.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] For example, at solar core temperature (*T* ≈ 15 MK) and density (160 g/cm3), the energy release rate is only 276 μW/cm3—about a quarter of the volumetric rate at which a resting human body generates heat.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Thus, reproduction of stellar core conditions in a lab for nuclear fusion power production is completely impractical.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Because nuclear reaction rates depend on density as well as temperature, and most fusion schemes operate at relatively low densities, those methods are strongly dependent on higher temperatures.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The fusion rate as a function of temperature (exp(−*E*/*kT*)), leads to the need to achieve temperatures in terrestrial reactors 10–100 times higher than in stellar interiors: *T* ≈ (0.1–1.0)×109 K.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In artificial fusion, the primary fuel is not constrained to be protons and higher temperatures can be used, so reactions with larger cross-sections are chosen.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Another concern is the production of neutrons, which activate the reactor structure radiologically, but also have the advantages of allowing volumetric extraction of the fusion energy and tritium breeding.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Reactions that release no neutrons are referred to as *aneutronic*.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] To be a useful energy source, a fusion reaction must satisfy several criteria.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] ) is directly related to the number of protons it contains – its atomic number.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] At anything less than stellar densities, three-body collisions are too improbable.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In inertial confinement, both stellar densities and temperatures are exceeded to compensate for the shortcomings of the third parameter of the Lawson criterion, ICF's very short confinement time.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This allows simultaneous conservation of energy and momentum without relying on the electromagnetic force.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The cross sections for the weak interaction are too small.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] For reactions with two products, the energy is divided between them in inverse proportion to their masses, as shown.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In most reactions with three products, the distribution of energy varies.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] For reactions that can result in more than one set of products, the branching ratios are given.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Some reaction candidates can be eliminated at once.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The D–6Li reaction has no advantage compared to p+–11 5B because it is roughly as difficult to burn but produces substantially more neutrons through 2 1D–2 1D side reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] There is also a p+–7 3Li reaction, but the cross section is far too low, except possibly when *T**i* > 1 MeV, but at such high temperatures an endothermic, direct neutron-producing reaction also becomes very significant.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Finally there is also a p+–9 4Be reaction, which is not only difficult to burn, but 9 4Be can be easily induced to split into two alpha particles and a neutron.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The latter of the two equations was unknown when the U.S. conducted the Castle Bravo fusion bomb test in 1954.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Being just the second fusion bomb ever tested (and the first to use lithium), the designers of the Castle Bravo "Shrimp" had understood the usefulness of 6Li in tritium production, but had failed to recognize that 7Li fission would greatly increase the yield of the bomb.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] While 7Li has a small neutron cross-section for low neutron energies, it has a higher cross section above 5 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The 15 Mt yield was 150% greater than the predicted 6 Mt and caused unexpected exposure to fallout.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] To evaluate the usefulness of these reactions, in addition to the reactants, the products, and the energy released, one needs to know something about the nuclear cross section.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Any given fusion device has a maximum plasma pressure it can sustain, and an economical device would always operate near this maximum.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Given this pressure, the largest fusion output is obtained when the temperature is chosen so that ⟨*σv*⟩/*T*2 is a maximum.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This is also the temperature at which the value of the triple product nTτ required for ignition is a minimum, since that required value is inversely proportional to ⟨*σv*⟩/*T*2 (see Lawson criterion).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] (A plasma is "ignited" if the fusion reactions produce enough power to maintain the temperature without external heating.) This optimum temperature and the value of ⟨*σv*⟩/*T*2 at that temperature is given for a few of these reactions in the following table.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Note that many of the reactions form chains.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] For instance, a reactor fueled with 3 1T and 3 2He creates some 2 1D, which is then possible to use in the 2 1D–3 2He reaction if the energies are "right".
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] An elegant idea is to combine the reactions (8) and (9).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The 3 2He from reaction (8) can react with 6 3Li in reaction (9) before completely thermalizing.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This produces an energetic proton, which in turn undergoes reaction (8) before thermalizing.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Detailed analysis shows that this idea would not work well, but it is a good example of a case where the usual assumption of a Maxwellian plasma is not appropriate.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Any of the reactions above can in principle be the basis of fusion power production.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In addition to the temperature and cross section discussed above, we must consider the total energy of the fusion products *E*fus, the energy of the charged fusion products *E*ch, and the atomic number *Z* of the non-hydrogenic reactant.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Specification of the 2 1D–2 1D reaction entails some difficulties, though.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] To begin with, one must average over the two branches (2i) and (2ii).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] More difficult is to decide how to treat the 3 1T and 3 2He products.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] 3 1T burns so well in a deuterium plasma that it is almost impossible to extract from the plasma.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The 2 1D–3 2He reaction is optimized at a much higher temperature, so the burnup at the optimum 2 1D–2 1D temperature may be low.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Another unique aspect of the 2 1D–2 1D reaction is that there is only one reactant, which must be taken into account when calculating the reaction rate.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The last column is the neutronicity of the reaction, the fraction of the fusion energy released as neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This is an important indicator of the magnitude of the problems associated with neutrons like radiation damage, biological shielding, remote handling, and safety.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] For the first two reactions it is calculated as (*E*fus − *E*ch)/*E*fus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] For the last two reactions, where this calculation would give zero, the values quoted are rough estimates based on side reactions that produce neutrons in a plasma in thermal equilibrium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Of course, the reactants should also be mixed in the optimal proportions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This is the case when each reactant ion plus its associated electrons accounts for half the pressure.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Assuming that the total pressure is fixed, this means that particle density of the non-hydrogenic ion is smaller than that of the hydrogenic ion by a factor 2/(*Z* + 1).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Therefore, the rate for these reactions is reduced by the same factor, on top of any differences in the values of ⟨*σv*⟩/*T*2.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] On the other hand, because the 2 1D–2 1D reaction has only one reactant, its rate is twice as high as when the fuel is divided between two different hydrogenic species, thus creating a more efficient reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Thus there is a "penalty" of 2/(*Z* + 1) for non-hydrogenic fuels arising from the fact that they require more electrons, which take up pressure without participating in the fusion reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] (It is usually a good assumption that the electron temperature will be nearly equal to the ion temperature.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Some authors, however, discuss the possibility that the electrons could be maintained substantially colder than the ions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In such a case, known as a "hot ion mode", the "penalty" would not apply.) There is at the same time a "bonus" of a factor 2 for 2 1D–2 1D because each ion can react with any of the other ions, not just a fraction of them.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] We can now compare these reactions in the following table.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The maximum value of ⟨*σv*⟩/*T*2 is taken from a previous table.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The "penalty/bonus" factor is that related to a non-hydrogenic reactant or a single-species reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The values in the column "inverse reactivity" are found by dividing 1.24×10−24 by the product of the second and third columns.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] It indicates the factor by which the other reactions occur more slowly than the 2 1D–3 1T reaction under comparable conditions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The column "Lawson criterion" weights these results with *E*ch and gives an indication of how much more difficult it is to achieve ignition with these reactions, relative to the difficulty for the 2 1D–3 1T reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The next-to-last column is labeled "power density" and weights the practical reactivity by *E*fus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The final column indicates how much lower the fusion power density of the other reactions is compared to the 2 1D–3 1T reaction and can be considered a measure of the economic potential.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The ions undergoing fusion in many systems will essentially never occur alone but will be mixed with electrons that in aggregate neutralize the ions' bulk electrical charge and form a plasma.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The electrons will generally have a temperature comparable to or greater than that of the ions, so they will collide with the ions and emit x-ray radiation of 10–30 keV energy, a process known as Bremsstrahlung.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The huge size of the Sun and stars means that the x-rays produced in this process will not escape and will deposit their energy back into the plasma.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] But any terrestrial fusion reactor will be optically thin for x-rays of this energy range.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] X-rays are difficult to reflect but they are effectively absorbed (and converted into heat) in less than mm thickness of stainless steel (which is part of a reactor's shield).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This means the bremsstrahlung process is carrying energy out of the plasma, cooling it.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The ratio of fusion power produced to x-ray radiation lost to walls is an important figure of merit.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This ratio is generally maximized at a much higher temperature than that which maximizes the power density (see the previous subsection).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The actual ratios of fusion to Bremsstrahlung power will likely be significantly lower for several reasons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] For one, the calculation assumes that the energy of the fusion products is transmitted completely to the fuel ions, which then lose energy to the electrons by collisions, which in turn lose energy by Bremsstrahlung.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] However, because the fusion products move much faster than the fuel ions, they will give up a significant fraction of their energy directly to the electrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Secondly, the ions in the plasma are assumed to be purely fuel ions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In practice, there will be a significant proportion of impurity ions, which will then lower the ratio.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In particular, the fusion products themselves *must* remain in the plasma until they have given up their energy, and *will* remain for some time after that in any proposed confinement scheme.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Finally, all channels of energy loss other than Bremsstrahlung have been neglected.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] On theoretical and experimental grounds, particle and energy confinement seem to be closely related.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In a confinement scheme that does a good job of retaining energy, fusion products will build up.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] If the fusion products are efficiently ejected, then energy confinement will be poor, too.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The temperatures maximizing the fusion power compared to the Bremsstrahlung are in every case higher than the temperature that maximizes the power density and minimizes the required value of the fusion triple product.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This will not change the optimum operating point for 2 1D–3 1T very much because the Bremsstrahlung fraction is low, but it will push the other fuels into regimes where the power density relative to 2 1D–3 1T is even lower and the required confinement even more difficult to achieve.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] For 2 1D–2 1D and 2 1D–3 2He, Bremsstrahlung losses will be a serious, possibly prohibitive problem.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] For 3 2He–3 2He, p+–6 3Li and p+–11 5B the Bremsstrahlung losses appear to make a fusion reactor using these fuels with a quasineutral, isotropic plasma impossible.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Some ways out of this dilemma have been considered but rejected.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This limitation does not apply to non-neutral and anisotropic plasmas; however, these have their own challenges to contend with.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In a classical picture, nuclei can be understood as hard spheres that repel each other through the Coulomb force but fuse once the two spheres come close enough for contact.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] This would imply that for the core of the sun, which has a Boltzmann distribution with a temperature of around 1.4 keV, the probability hydrogen would reach the threshold is 10−290, that is, fusion would never occur.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] However, fusion in the sun does occur due to quantum mechanics.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The probability that fusion occurs is greatly increased compared to the classical picture, thanks to the smearing of the effective radius as the de Broglie wavelength as well as quantum tunneling through the potential barrier.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] To determine the rate of fusion reactions, the value of most interest is the cross section, which describes the probability that particles will fuse by giving a characteristic area of interaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] where $\sigma _{\text{geometry}}$ is the geometric cross section, T is the barrier transparency and R is the reaction characteristics of the reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] R contains all the nuclear physics of the specific reaction and takes very different values depending on the nature of the interaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] However, for most reactions, the variation of $R(\epsilon )$ is small compared to the variation from the Gamow factor and so is approximated by a function called the astrophysical S-factor, $S(\epsilon )$ , which is weakly varying in energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] More detailed forms of the cross-section can be derived through nuclear physics-based models and R-matrix theory.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] Bosch-Hale also reports a R-matrix calculated cross sections fitting observation data with Padé rational approximating coefficients.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In fusion systems that are in thermal equilibrium, the particles are in a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution, meaning the particles have a range of energies centered around the plasma temperature.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The sun, magnetically confined plasmas and inertial confinement fusion systems are well modeled to be in thermal equilibrium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] In these cases, the value of interest is the fusion cross-section averaged across the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-fusion-p02] The Naval Research Lab's plasma physics formulary tabulates Maxwell averaged fusion cross sections reactivities in $\mathrm {cm^{3}/s}$ .
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Nuclear physics should not be confused with atomic physics, which studies the atom as a whole, including its electrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Discoveries in nuclear physics have led to applications in many fields such as nuclear power, nuclear weapons, nuclear medicine and magnetic resonance imaging, industrial and agricultural isotopes, ion implantation in materials engineering, and radiocarbon dating in geology and archaeology.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Such applications are studied in the field of nuclear engineering.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Particle physics evolved out of nuclear physics and the two fields are typically taught in close association.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Nuclear astrophysics, the application of nuclear physics to astrophysics, is crucial in explaining the inner workings of stars and the origin of the chemical elements.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The history of nuclear physics as a discipline distinct from atomic physics, starts with the discovery of radioactivity by Henri Becquerel in 1896, made while investigating phosphorescence in uranium salts.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Thomson a year later was an indication that the atom had internal structure.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] At the beginning of the 20th century the accepted model of the atom was J.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Thomson's "plum pudding" model in which the atom was a positively charged ball with smaller negatively charged electrons embedded inside it.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In the years that followed, radioactivity was extensively investigated, notably by Marie Curie, a Polish physicist whose maiden name was Sklodowska, Pierre Curie, Ernest Rutherford and others.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] By the turn of the century, physicists had also discovered three types of radiation emanating from atoms, which they named alpha, beta, and gamma radiation.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Experiments by Otto Hahn in 1911 and by James Chadwick in 1914 discovered that the beta decay spectrum was continuous rather than discrete.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] That is, electrons were ejected from the atom with a continuous range of energies, rather than the discrete amounts of energy that were observed in gamma and alpha decays.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] This was a problem for nuclear physics at the time, because it seemed to indicate that energy was not conserved in these decays.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The 1903 Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded jointly to Becquerel, for his discovery and to Marie and Pierre Curie for their subsequent research into radioactivity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Rutherford was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1908 for his "investigations into the disintegration of the elements and the chemistry of radioactive substances".
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In 1905, Albert Einstein formulated the idea of mass–energy equivalence.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] While the work on radioactivity by Becquerel and Marie Curie predates this, an explanation of the source of the energy of radioactivity would have to wait for the discovery that the nucleus itself was composed of smaller constituents, the nucleons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In 1906, Ernest Rutherford published "Retardation of the a Particle from Radium in passing through matter." Hans Geiger expanded on this work in a communication to the Royal Society with experiments he and Rutherford had done, passing alpha particles through air, aluminum foil and gold leaf.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] More work was published in 1909 by Geiger and Ernest Marsden, and further greatly expanded work was published in 1910 by Geiger.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In 1911–1912 Rutherford went before the Royal Society to explain the experiments and propound the new theory of the atomic nucleus as we now understand it.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Published in 1909, with the eventual classical analysis by Rutherford published May 1911, the key preemptive experiment was performed during 1909, at the University of Manchester.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Ernest Rutherford's assistant, Professor Johannes "Hans" Geiger, and an undergraduate, Marsden, performed an experiment in which Geiger and Marsden under Rutherford's supervision fired alpha particles (helium 4 nuclei) at a thin film of gold foil.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The plum pudding model had predicted that the alpha particles should come out of the foil with their trajectories being at most slightly bent.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] But Rutherford instructed his team to look for something that shocked him to observe: a few particles were scattered through large angles, even completely backwards in some cases.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] He likened it to firing a bullet at tissue paper and having it bounce off.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] As an example, in this model (which is not the modern one) nitrogen-14 consisted of a nucleus with 14 protons and 7 electrons (21 total particles) and the nucleus was surrounded by 7 more orbiting electrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] At that time, the source of stellar energy was a complete mystery; Eddington correctly speculated that the source was fusion of hydrogen into helium, liberating enormous energy according to Einstein's equation *E = mc2*.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] This was a particularly remarkable development since at that time fusion and thermonuclear energy, and even that stars are largely composed of hydrogen (see metallicity), had not yet been discovered.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The Rutherford model worked quite well until studies of nuclear spin were carried out by Franco Rasetti at the California Institute of Technology in 1929.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] By 1925 it was known that protons and electrons each had a spin of ±+1⁄2.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In the Rutherford model of nitrogen-14, 20 of the total 21 nuclear particles should have paired up to cancel each other's spin, and the final odd particle should have left the nucleus with a net spin of 1⁄2.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Rasetti discovered, however, that nitrogen-14 had a spin of 1.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In the same year Dmitri Ivanenko suggested that there were no electrons in the nucleus — only protons and neutrons — and that neutrons were spin 1⁄2 particles, which explained the mass not due to protons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The neutron spin immediately solved the problem of the spin of nitrogen-14, as the one unpaired proton and one unpaired neutron in this model each contributed a spin of 1⁄2 in the same direction, giving a final total spin of 1.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] With the discovery of the neutron, scientists could at last calculate what fraction of binding energy each nucleus had, by comparing the nuclear mass with that of the protons and neutrons which composed it.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Differences between nuclear masses were calculated in this way.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] When nuclear reactions were measured, these were found to agree with Einstein's calculation of the equivalence of mass and energy to within 1% as of 1934.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Alexandru Proca was the first to develop and report the massive vector boson field equations and a theory of the mesonic field of nuclear forces.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In 1935 Hideki Yukawa proposed the first significant theory of the strong force to explain how the nucleus holds together.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In the Yukawa interaction a virtual particle, later called a meson, mediated a force between all nucleons, including protons and neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] This force explained why nuclei did not disintegrate under the influence of proton repulsion, and it also gave an explanation of why the attractive strong force had a more limited range than the electromagnetic repulsion between protons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Later, the discovery of the pi meson showed it to have the properties of Yukawa's particle.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] With Yukawa's papers, the modern model of the atom was complete.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The center of the atom contains a tight ball of neutrons and protons, which is held together by the strong nuclear force, unless it is too large.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Unstable nuclei may undergo alpha decay, in which they emit an energetic helium nucleus, or beta decay, in which they eject an electron (or positron).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] After one of these decays the resultant nucleus may be left in an excited state, and in this case it decays to its ground state by emitting high-energy photons (gamma decay).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The study of the strong and weak nuclear forces (the latter explained by Enrico Fermi via Fermi's interaction in 1934) led physicists to collide nuclei and electrons at ever higher energies.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] This research became the science of particle physics, the crown jewel of which is the standard model of particle physics, which describes the strong, weak, and electromagnetic forces.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] A heavy nucleus can contain hundreds of nucleons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] This means that with some approximation it can be treated as a classical system, rather than a quantum-mechanical one.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In the resulting liquid-drop model, the nucleus has an energy that arises partly from surface tension and partly from electrical repulsion of the protons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The liquid-drop model is able to reproduce many features of nuclei, including the general trend of binding energy with respect to mass number, as well as the phenomenon of nuclear fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Superimposed on this classical picture, however, are quantum-mechanical effects, which can be described using the nuclear shell model, developed in large part by Maria Goeppert Mayer and J.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Nuclei with certain "magic" numbers of neutrons and protons are particularly stable, because their shells are filled.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Other more complicated models for the nucleus have also been proposed, such as the interacting boson model, in which pairs of neutrons and protons interact as bosons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Ab initio methods try to solve the nuclear many-body problem from the ground up, starting from the nucleons and their interactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Much of current research in nuclear physics relates to the study of nuclei under extreme conditions such as high spin and excitation energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Nuclei may also have extreme shapes (similar to that of Rugby balls or even pears) or extreme neutron-to-proton ratios.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Experimenters can create such nuclei using artificially induced fusion or nucleon transfer reactions, employing ion beams from an accelerator.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Eighty elements have at least one stable isotope which is never observed to decay, amounting to a total of about 251 stable nuclides.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] However, thousands of isotopes have been characterized as unstable.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] These "radioisotopes" decay over time scales ranging from fractions of a second to trillions of years.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Plotted on a chart as a function of atomic and neutron numbers, the binding energy of the nuclides forms what is known as the valley of stability.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Stable nuclides lie along the bottom of this energy valley, while increasingly unstable nuclides lie up the valley walls, that is, have weaker binding energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The most stable nuclei fall within certain ranges or balances of composition of neutrons and protons: too few or too many neutrons (in relation to the number of protons) will cause it to decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] For example, in beta decay, a nitrogen-16 atom (7 protons, 9 neutrons) is converted to an oxygen-16 atom (8 protons, 8 neutrons) within a few seconds of being created.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In this decay a neutron in the nitrogen nucleus is converted by the weak interaction into a proton, an electron and an antineutrino.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The element is transmuted to another element, with a different number of protons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In alpha decay, which typically occurs in the heaviest nuclei, the radioactive element decays by emitting a helium nucleus (2 protons and 2 neutrons), giving another element, plus helium-4.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In many cases this process continues through several steps of this kind, including other types of decays (usually beta decay) until a stable element is formed.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In gamma decay, a nucleus decays from an excited state into a lower energy state, by emitting a gamma ray.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The element is not changed to another element in the process (no nuclear transmutation is involved).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Other more exotic decays are possible (see the first main article).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] For example, in internal conversion decay, the energy from an excited nucleus may eject one of the inner orbital electrons from the atom, in a process which produces high speed electrons but is not beta decay and (unlike beta decay) does not transmute one element to another.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In nuclear fusion, two low-mass nuclei come into very close contact with each other so that the strong force fuses them.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] It requires a large amount of energy for the strong or nuclear forces to overcome the electrical repulsion between the nuclei in order to fuse them; therefore nuclear fusion can only take place at very high temperatures or high pressures.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] When nuclei fuse, a very large amount of energy is released and the combined nucleus assumes a lower energy level.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The binding energy per nucleon increases with mass number up to nickel-62.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Stars like the Sun are powered by the fusion of four protons into a helium nucleus, two positrons, and two neutrinos.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The uncontrolled fusion of hydrogen into helium is known as thermonuclear runaway.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] A frontier in current research at various institutions, for example the Joint European Torus (JET) and ITER, is the development of an economically viable method of using energy from a controlled fusion reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Nuclear fusion is the origin of the energy (including in the form of light and other electromagnetic radiation) produced by the core of all stars including our own Sun.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Nuclear fission is the reverse process to fusion.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] For nuclei heavier than nickel-62 the binding energy per nucleon decreases with the mass number.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] It is therefore possible for energy to be released if a heavy nucleus breaks apart into two lighter ones.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The process of alpha decay is in essence a special type of spontaneous nuclear fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] It is a highly asymmetrical fission because the four particles which make up the alpha particle are especially tightly bound to each other, making production of this nucleus in fission particularly likely.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] From several of the heaviest nuclei whose fission produces free neutrons, and which also easily absorb neutrons to initiate fission, a self-igniting type of neutron-initiated fission can be obtained, in a chain reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Chain reactions were known in chemistry before physics, and in fact many familiar processes like fires and chemical explosions are chemical chain reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The fission or "nuclear" chain-reaction, using fission-produced neutrons, is the source of energy for nuclear power plants and fission-type nuclear bombs, such as those detonated in Hiroshima and Nagasaki, Japan, at the end of World War II.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Heavy nuclei such as uranium and thorium may also undergo spontaneous fission, but they are much more likely to undergo decay by alpha decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] For a neutron-initiated chain reaction to occur, there must be a critical mass of the relevant isotope present in a certain space under certain conditions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The conditions for the smallest critical mass require the conservation of the emitted neutrons and also their slowing or moderation so that there is a greater cross-section or probability of them initiating another fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] In two regions of Oklo, Gabon, Africa, natural nuclear fission reactors were active over 1.5 billion years ago.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Measurements of natural neutrino emission have demonstrated that around half of the heat emanating from the Earth's core results from radioactive decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] However, it is not known if any of this results from fission chain reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] According to the theory, as the Universe cooled after the Big Bang it eventually became possible for common subatomic particles as we know them (neutrons, protons and electrons) to exist.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The most common particles created in the Big Bang which are still easily observable to us today were protons and electrons (in equal numbers).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The protons would eventually form hydrogen atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Almost all the neutrons created in the Big Bang were absorbed into helium-4 in the first three minutes after the Big Bang, and this helium accounts for most of the helium in the universe today (see Big Bang nucleosynthesis).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Progressively heavier elements are created during the evolution of a star.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Energy is only released in fusion processes involving smaller atoms than iron because the binding energy per nucleon peaks around iron (56 nucleons).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Since the creation of heavier nuclei by fusion requires energy, nature resorts to the process of neutron capture.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] Neutrons (due to their lack of charge) are readily absorbed by a nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The heavy elements are created by either a *slow* neutron capture process (the so-called *s*-process) or the *rapid*, or *r*-process.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The *s* process occurs in thermally pulsing stars (called AGB, or asymptotic giant branch stars) and takes hundreds to thousands of years to reach the heaviest elements of lead and bismuth.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] The *r*-process is thought to occur in supernova explosions, which provide the necessary conditions of high temperature, high neutron flux and ejected matter.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-physics] These stellar conditions make the successive neutron captures very fast, involving very neutron-rich species which then beta-decay to heavier elements, especially at the so-called waiting points that correspond to more stable nuclides with closed neutron shells (magic numbers).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] In nuclear physics and nuclear chemistry, a **nuclear reaction** is a process in which two nuclei, or a nucleus and an external subatomic particle, collide to produce one or more new nuclides.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Thus, a nuclear reaction must cause a transformation of at least one nuclide to another.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] If a nucleus interacts with another nucleus or particle, and they then separate without changing the nature of any nuclide, the process is simply referred to as a type of nuclear scattering, rather than a nuclear reaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] The term "nuclear reaction" may refer either to a change in a nuclide **induced** by collision with another particle or to a **spontaneous** change of a nuclide without collision.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Natural nuclear reactions occur in the interaction between cosmic rays and matter, and nuclear reactions can be employed artificially to obtain nuclear energy, at an adjustable rate, on-demand.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Nuclear chain reactions in fissionable materials produce induced nuclear fission.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Various nuclear fusion reactions of light elements power the energy production of the Sun and stars.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Most nuclear reactions (fusion and fission) results in transmutation of nuclei (called also nuclear transmutation).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] In 1919, Ernest Rutherford was able to accomplish transmutation of nitrogen into oxygen at the University of Manchester, using alpha particles directed at nitrogen 14N + α → 17O + p.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] This was the first observation of an induced nuclear reaction, that is, a reaction in which particles from one decay are used to transform another atomic nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Eventually, in 1932 at Cambridge University, a fully artificial nuclear reaction and nuclear transmutation was achieved by Rutherford's colleagues John Cockcroft and Ernest Walton, who used artificially accelerated protons against lithium-7, to split the nucleus into two alpha particles.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] The feat was popularly known as "splitting the atom", although it was not the modern nuclear fission reaction later (in 1938) discovered in heavy elements by the German scientists Otto Hahn, Lise Meitner, and Fritz Strassmann.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Nuclear reactions may be shown in a form similar to chemical equations, for which invariant mass must balance for each side of the equation, and in which transformations of particles must follow certain conservation laws, such as conservation of charge and baryon number (total atomic mass number).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] To balance the equation above for mass, charge and mass number, the second nucleus to the right must have atomic number 2 and mass number 4; it is therefore also helium-4.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Instead of using the full equations in the style above, in many situations a compact notation is used to describe nuclear reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] This style of the form A(b,c)D is equivalent to A + b producing c + D.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Common light particles are often abbreviated in this shorthand, typically p for proton, n for neutron, d for deuteron, α representing an alpha particle or helium-4, β for beta particle or electron, γ for gamma photon, etc.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] The reaction above would be written as 6Li(d,α)α.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Kinetic energy may be released during the course of a reaction (exothermic reaction) or kinetic energy may have to be supplied for the reaction to take place (endothermic reaction).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] This can be calculated by reference to a table of very accurate particle rest masses, as follows: according to the reference tables, the 6 3Li nucleus has a standard atomic weight of 6.015 daltons (symbol Da), the deuterium has 2.014 Da, and the helium-4 nucleus has 4.0026 Da.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] In a nuclear reaction, the total (relativistic) energy is conserved.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] The "missing" rest mass must therefore reappear as kinetic energy released in the reaction; its source is the nuclear binding energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Using Einstein's mass-energy equivalence formula *E* = *mc*2, the amount of energy released can be determined.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Expressed differently: the mass is reduced by 0.3%, corresponding to 0.3% of 90 PJ/kg is 270 TJ/kg.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] This is a large amount of energy for a nuclear reaction; the amount is so high because the binding energy per nucleon of the helium-4 nucleus is unusually high because the He-4 nucleus is "doubly magic".
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Consequently, alpha particles appear frequently on the right-hand side of nuclear reactions.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] When the product nucleus is metastable, this is indicated by placing an asterisk ("*") next to its atomic number.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] This energy is eventually released through nuclear decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] A small amount of energy may also emerge in the form of X-rays.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Generally, the product nucleus has a different atomic number, and thus the configuration of its electron shells is wrong.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] As the electrons rearrange themselves and drop to lower energy levels, internal transition X-rays (X-rays with precisely defined emission lines) may be emitted.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] For the particular case discussed above, the reaction energy has already been calculated as *Q* = 22.2 MeV.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] The reaction energy (the "Q-value") is positive for exothermal reactions and negative for endothermal reactions, opposite to the similar expression in chemistry.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] On the one hand, it is the difference between the sums of kinetic energies on the final side and on the initial side.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] But on the other hand, it is also the difference between the nuclear rest masses on the initial side and on the final side (in this way, we have calculated the Q-value above).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] If the reaction equation is balanced, that does not mean that the reaction really occurs.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] The rate at which reactions occur depends on the energy and the flux of the incident particles, and the reaction cross section.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] An example of a large repository of reaction rates is the REACLIB database, as maintained by the Joint Institute for Nuclear Astrophysics.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] In the initial collision which begins the reaction, the particles must approach closely enough so that the short-range strong force can affect them.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] As most common nuclear particles are positively charged, this means they must overcome considerable electrostatic repulsion before the reaction can begin.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Even if the target nucleus is part of a neutral atom, the other particle must penetrate well beyond the electron cloud and closely approach the nucleus, which is positively charged.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Also, since the force of repulsion is proportional to the product of the two charges, reactions between heavy nuclei are rarer, and require higher initiating energy, than those between a heavy and light nucleus; while reactions between two light nuclei are the most common ones.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Neutrons, on the other hand, have no electric charge to cause repulsion, and are able to initiate a nuclear reaction at very low energies.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] In fact, at extremely low particle energies (corresponding, say, to thermal equilibrium at room temperature), the neutron's de Broglie wavelength is greatly increased, possibly greatly increasing its capture cross-section, at energies close to resonances of the nuclei involved.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Thus low-energy neutrons *may* be even more reactive than high-energy neutrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] While the number of possible nuclear reactions is immense, there are several types that are more common, or otherwise notable.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] An intermediate energy projectile transfers energy or picks up or loses nucleons to the nucleus in a single quick (10−21 second) event.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Energy and momentum transfer are relatively small.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] These are particularly useful in experimental nuclear physics, because the reaction mechanisms are often simple enough to calculate with sufficient accuracy to probe the structure of the target nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Only energy and momentum are transferred.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Energy and charge are transferred between projectile and target.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Usually at moderately low energy, one or more nucleons are transferred between the projectile and target.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] These are useful in studying outer shell structure of nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Reactions with neutrons are important in nuclear reactors and nuclear weapons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] Either a low-energy projectile is absorbed or a higher energy particle transfers energy to the nucleus, leaving it with too much energy to be fully bound together.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] On a time scale of about 10−19 seconds, particles, usually neutrons, are "boiled" off.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] That is, it remains together until enough energy happens to be concentrated in one neutron to escape the mutual attraction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-reaction] The excited quasi-bound nucleus is called a **compound nucleus**.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] In nuclear physics, atomic physics, and nuclear chemistry, the **nuclear shell model** utilizes the Pauli exclusion principle to model the structure of atomic nuclei in terms of energy levels.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The first shell model was proposed by Dmitri Ivanenko (together with E.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The model was developed in 1949 following independent work by several physicists, most notably Maria Goeppert Mayer and J.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Jensen, who received the 1963 Nobel Prize in Physics for their contributions to this model, and Eugene Wigner, who received the Nobel Prize alongside them for his earlier foundational work on atomic nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The nuclear shell model is partly analogous to the atomic shell model, which describes the arrangement of electrons in an atom, in that a filled shell results in better stability.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] When adding nucleons (protons and neutrons) to a nucleus, there are certain points where the binding energy of the next nucleon is significantly less than the last one.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This observation that there are specific magic quantum numbers of nucleons (**2, 8, 20, 28, 50, 82, and 126**) that are more tightly bound than the following higher number is the origin of the shell model.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The shells for protons and neutrons are independent of each other.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Therefore, there can exist both "magic nuclei", in which one nucleon type or the other is at a magic number, and "doubly magic quantum nuclei", where both are.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Due to variations in orbital filling, the upper magic numbers are 126 and, speculatively, 184 for neutrons, but only 114 for protons, playing a role in the search for the so-called island of stability.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Some semi-magic numbers have been found, notably *Z* = 40, which gives the nuclear shell filling for the various elements; 16 may also be a magic number.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] To get these numbers, the nuclear shell model starts with an average potential with a shape somewhere between the square well and the harmonic oscillator.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] To this potential, a spin-orbit term is added.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Even so, the total perturbation does not coincide with the experiment, and an empirical spin-orbit coupling must be added with at least two or three different values of its coupling constant, depending on the nuclei being studied.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The magic numbers of nuclei, as well as other properties, can be arrived at by approximating the model with a three-dimensional harmonic oscillator plus a spin–orbit interaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] A more realistic but complicated potential is known as the Woods–Saxon potential.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Consider a three-dimensional harmonic oscillator.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This means that the magic numbers are expected to be those in which all occupied shells are full.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] In accordance with the experiment, we get 2 (level 0 full) and 8 (levels 0 and 1 full) for the first two numbers.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] However, the full set of magic numbers does not turn out correctly.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] where for every *ℓ* there are 2*ℓ*+1 different values of *ml* and 2 values of *ms*, giving a total of 4*ℓ*+2 states for every specific level.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] These numbers are twice the values of triangular numbers from the Pascal Triangle: 1, 3, 6, 10, 15, 21, ....
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] We next include a spin–orbit interaction.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] First, we have to describe the system by the quantum numbers *j*, *mj* and parity instead of *ℓ*, *ml* and *ms*, as in the hydrogen–like atom.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Since every even level includes only even values of *ℓ*, it includes only states of even (positive) parity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Similarly, every odd level includes only states of odd (negative) parity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Thus we can ignore parity in counting states.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] where for every *j* there are 2*j*+1 different states from different values of *mj*.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Due to the spin–orbit interaction, the energies of states of the same level but with different *j* will no longer be identical.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This is because in the original quantum numbers, when $\scriptstyle {\vec {s}}$ is parallel to $\scriptstyle {\vec {l}}$ , the interaction energy is positive, and in this case *j* = *ℓ* + *s* = *ℓ* + ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] When $\scriptstyle {\vec {s}}$ is anti-parallel to $\scriptstyle {\vec {l}}$ (i.e. aligned oppositely), the interaction energy is negative, and in this case *j*=*ℓ*−*s*=*ℓ*−⁠1/2⁠.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Furthermore, the strength of the interaction is roughly proportional to *ℓ*.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The harmonic oscillator potential $V(r)=\mu \omega ^{2}r^{2}/2$ grows infinitely as the distance from the center *r* goes to infinity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] A more realistic potential, such as the Woods–Saxon potential, would approach a constant at this limit.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] One main consequence is that the average radius of nucleons' orbits would be larger in a realistic potential.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This leads to a reduced term $\scriptstyle \hbar ^{2}l(l+1)/2mr^{2}$ in the Laplace operator of the Hamiltonian operator.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Another main difference is that orbits with high average radii, such as those with high *n* or high *ℓ*, will have a lower energy than in a harmonic oscillator potential.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Both effects lead to a reduction in the energy levels of high *ℓ* orbits.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Together with the spin–orbit interaction, and for appropriate magnitudes of both effects, one is led to the following qualitative picture: at all levels, the highest *j* states have their energies shifted downwards, especially for high *n* (where the highest *j* is high).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This is both due to the negative spin–orbit interaction energy and to the reduction in energy resulting from deforming the potential into a more realistic one.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The second-to-highest *j* states, on the contrary, have their energy shifted up by the first effect and down by the second effect, leading to a small overall shift.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The shifts in the energy of the highest *j* states can thus bring the energy of states of one level closer to the energy of states of a lower level.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The "shells" of the shell model are then no longer identical to the levels denoted by *n*, and the magic numbers are changed.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] We may then suppose that the highest *j* states for *n* = 3 have an intermediate energy between the average energies of *n* = 2 and *n* = 3, and suppose that the highest *j* states for larger *n* (at least up to *n* = 7) have an energy closer to the average energy of *n*−1.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Note that the numbers of states after the 4th shell are doubled triangular numbers *plus two*.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Spin–orbit coupling causes so-called "intruder levels" to drop down from the next higher shell into the structure of the previous shell.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The sizes of the intruders are such that the resulting shell sizes are themselves increased to the next higher doubled triangular numbers from those of the harmonic oscillator.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] For example, 1f2p has 20 nucleons, and spin–orbit coupling adds 1g9/2 (10 nucleons), leading to a new shell with 30 nucleons.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] 1g2d3s has 30 nucleons, and adding intruder 1h11/2 (12 nucleons) yields a new shell size of 42, and so on.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This gives all the observed magic numbers and also predicts a new one (the so-called *island of stability*) at the value of 184 (for protons, the magic number 126 has not been observed yet, and more complicated theoretical considerations predict the magic number to be 114 instead).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Another way to predict magic (and semi-magic) numbers is by laying out the idealized filling order (with spin–orbit splitting but energy levels not overlapping).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] For consistency, s is split into *j* = ⁠1/2⁠ and *j* = −⁠1/2⁠ components with 2 and 0 members respectively.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Taking the leftmost and rightmost total counts within sequences bounded by / here gives the magic and semi-magic numbers.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This model also predicts or explains with some success other properties of nuclei, in particular spin and parity of nuclei ground states, and to some extent their excited nuclear states as well.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Take 17 8O (oxygen-17) as an example: Its nucleus has eight protons filling the first three proton "shells", eight neutrons filling the first three neutron "shells", and one extra neutron.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] All protons in a complete proton shell have zero total angular momentum, since their angular momenta cancel each other.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] All protons in the same level (*n*) have the same parity (either +1 or −1), and since the parity of a pair of particles is the product of their parities, an even number of protons from the same level (*n*) will have +1 parity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Thus, the total angular momentum of the eight protons and the first eight neutrons is zero, and their total parity is +1.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This means that the spin (i.e. angular momentum) of the nucleus, as well as its parity, are fully determined by that of the ninth neutron.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This one is in the first (i.e. lowest energy) state of the 4th shell, which is a d-shell (*ℓ* = 2), and since *p* = (−1)*ℓ*, this gives the nucleus an overall parity of +1.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This 4th d-shell has a *j* = ⁠5/2⁠, thus the nucleus of 17 8O is expected to have positive parity and total angular momentum ⁠5/2⁠, which indeed it has.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] For further clarification on the notation refer to the article on the Russell–Saunders term symbol.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] For nuclei farther from the magic quantum numbers one must add the assumption that due to the relation between the strong nuclear force and total angular momentum, protons or neutrons with the same *n* tend to form pairs of opposite angular momentum.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Therefore, a nucleus with an even number of protons and an even number of neutrons has 0 spin and positive parity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] A nucleus with an even number of protons and an odd number of neutrons (or vice versa) has the parity of the last neutron (or proton), and the spin equal to the total angular momentum of this neutron (or proton).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] By "last" we mean the properties coming from the highest energy level.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] In the case of a nucleus with an odd number of protons and an odd number of neutrons, one must consider the total angular momentum and parity of both the last neutron and the last proton.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The nucleus parity will be a product of theirs, while the nucleus spin will be one of the possible results of the sum of their angular momenta (with other possible results being excited states of the nucleus).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] For nucleon pairs, however, it is often energetically favourable to be at high angular momentum, even if its energy level for a single nucleon would be higher.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This is due to the relation between angular momentum and the strong nuclear force.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The nuclear magnetic moment of neutrons and protons is partly predicted by this simple version of the shell model.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The magnetic moment is calculated through *j*, *ℓ* and *s* of the "last" nucleon, but nuclei are not in states of well-defined *ℓ* and *s*.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Furthermore, for odd-odd nuclei, one has to consider the two "last" nucleons, as in deuterium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Therefore, one gets several possible answers for the nuclear magnetic moment, one for each possible combined *ℓ* and *s* state, and the real state of the nucleus is a superposition of them.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Thus the real (measured) nuclear magnetic moment is somewhere in between the possible answers.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The electric dipole of a nucleus is always zero, because its ground state has a definite parity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The matter density (*ψ*2, where *ψ* is the wavefunction) is always invariant under parity.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This is usually the situation with the atomic electric dipole.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Higher electric and magnetic multipole moments cannot be predicted by this simple version of the shell model for reasons similar to those in the case of deuterium.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] For nuclei having two or more valence nucleons (i.e. nucleons outside a closed shell), a residual two-body interaction must be added.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This residual term comes from the part of the inter-nucleon interaction not included in the approximative average potential.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Through this inclusion, different shell configurations are mixed, and the energy degeneracy of states corresponding to the same configuration is broken.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] These residual interactions are incorporated through shell model calculations in a truncated model space (or valence space).
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This space is spanned by a basis of many-particle states where only single-particle states in the model space are active.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The Schrödinger equation is solved on this basis, using an effective Hamiltonian specifically suited for the model space.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This Hamiltonian is different from the one of free nucleons as, among other things, it has to compensate for excluded configurations.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] One can do away with the average potential approximation entirely by extending the model space to the previously inert core and treating all single-particle states up to the model space truncation as active.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This forms the basis of the **no-core shell model**, which is an ab initio method.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] It is necessary to include a three-body interaction in such calculations to achieve agreement with experiments.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] In 1953 the first experimental examples were found of rotational bands in nuclei, with their energy levels following the same J(J+1) pattern of energies as in rotating molecules.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Quantum mechanically, it is impossible to have a collective rotation of a sphere, so this implied that the shape of these nuclei was non-spherical.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] In principle, these rotational states could have been described as coherent superpositions of particle-hole excitations in the basis consisting of single-particle states of the spherical potential.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] But in reality, the description of these states in this manner is intractable, due to a large number of valence particles—and this intractability was even greater in the 1950s when computing power was extremely rudimentary.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] For these reasons, Aage Bohr, Ben Mottelson, and Sven Gösta Nilsson constructed models in which the potential was deformed into an ellipsoidal shape.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The first successful model of this type is now known as the Nilsson model.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] It is essentially the harmonic oscillator model described in this article, but with anisotropy added, so the oscillator frequencies along the three Cartesian axes are not all the same.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Typically the shape is a prolate ellipsoid, with the axis of symmetry taken to be z.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Because the potential is not spherically symmetric, the single-particle states are not states of good angular momentum J.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] However, a Lagrange multiplier $-\omega \cdot J$ , known as a "cranking" term, can be added to the Hamiltonian.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Usually the angular frequency vector ω is taken to be perpendicular to the symmetry axis, although tilted-axis cranking can also be considered.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Filling the single-particle states up to the Fermi level produces states whose expected angular momentum along the cranking axis $\langle J_{x}\rangle$ is the desired value.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Igal Talmi developed a method to obtain the information from experimental data and use it to calculate and predict energies which have not been measured.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This method has been successfully used by many nuclear physicists and has led to a deeper understanding of nuclear structure.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] The theory which gives a good description of these properties was developed.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] This description turned out to furnish the shell model basis of the elegant and successful interacting boson model.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] A model derived from the nuclear shell model is the alpha particle model developed by Henry Margenau, Edward Teller, J.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Skyrme, also sometimes called the Skyrme model.
[src:nuclear-physics/nuclear-shell-model] Note, however, that the Skyrme model is usually taken to be a model of the nucleon itself, as a "cloud" of mesons (pions), rather than as a model of the nucleus as a "cloud" of alpha particles.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Radioactive decay is a random process at the level of single atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] According to quantum theory, it is impossible to predict when a particular atom will decay, regardless of how long the atom has existed.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] However, for a significant number of identical atoms, the overall decay rate can be expressed as a decay constant or as a half-life.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The half-lives of radioactive atoms have a huge range: from nearly instantaneous to far longer than the age of the universe.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The decaying nucleus is called the parent radionuclide (or parent radioisotope), and the process produces at least one daughter nuclide.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Except for gamma decay or internal conversion from a nuclear excited state, the decay is a nuclear transmutation resulting in a daughter containing a different number of protons or neutrons (or both).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] When the number of protons changes, an atom of a different chemical element is created.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] There are 28 naturally occurring chemical elements on Earth that are radioactive, consisting of 35 radionuclides (seven elements have two different radionuclides each) that date before the time of formation of the Solar System.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] These 35 are known as primordial radionuclides.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Well-known examples are uranium and thorium, but also included are naturally occurring long-lived radioisotopes, such as potassium-40.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Each of the heavy primordial radionuclides participates in one of the four decay chains.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Henri Poincaré laid the seeds for the discovery of radioactivity through his interest in and studies of X-rays, which significantly influenced physicist Henri Becquerel.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Radioactivity was discovered in 1896 by Becquerel and independently by Marie Curie, while working with phosphorescent materials.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] These materials glow in the dark after exposure to light, and Becquerel suspected that the glow produced in cathode-ray tubes by X-rays might be associated with phosphorescence.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] He wrapped a photographic plate in black paper and placed various phosphorescent salts on it.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] All results were negative until he used uranium salts.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The uranium salts caused a blackening of the plate in spite of the plate being wrapped in black paper.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Curie named the radiation *rayons de Becquerel*, "Becquerel Rays" and showed that these rays were a property of atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] While X-rays were produced using electrical energy, the source of energy for radiation was a mystery.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In 1899, Julius Elster and Hans Geitel performed key experiments to find the energy source for radioactivity, excluding extraction of energy from air by measurements in a vacuum and extraction of energy from outer space by measurements 300m down a mine in the Harz mountains.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] If the atoms themselves were the source of energy, this meant the seemingly immutable atoms must be altered when emitting the rays.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In 1900 Curie summarized the puzzle of radioactivity as a choice between two equally unlikely possibilities: either energy was not conserved or chemical elements could be transmuted.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Rutherford was the first to realize that all such elements decay in accordance with the same mathematical exponential formula.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Rutherford and his student Frederick Soddy were the first to realize that many decay processes resulted in the transmutation of one element to another.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Subsequently, the radioactive displacement law of Fajans and Soddy was formulated to describe the products of alpha and beta decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The early researchers also discovered that many other chemical elements, besides uranium, have radioactive isotopes.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] A systematic search for the total radioactivity in uranium ores also guided Pierre and Marie Curie to isolate two new elements: polonium and radium.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Except for the radioactivity of radium, the chemical similarity of radium to barium made these two elements difficult to distinguish.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Marie and Pierre Curie also coined the term "radioactivity" to define the emission of ionizing radiation by some heavy elements.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] (Later the term was generalized to all elements.) Their research on the penetrating rays in uranium and the discovery of radium launched an era of using radium for the treatment of cancer.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Their exploration of radium could be seen as the first peaceful use of nuclear energy and the start of modern nuclear medicine.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The dangers of ionizing radiation due to radioactivity and X-rays were not immediately recognized.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The discovery of X‑rays by Wilhelm Röntgen in 1895 led to widespread experimentation by scientists, physicians, and inventors.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Many people began recounting stories of burns, hair loss and worse in technical journals as early as 1896.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In February of that year, Professor Daniel and Dr.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Dudley of Vanderbilt University performed an experiment involving X-raying Dudley's head that resulted in his hair loss.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Hawks, of his suffering severe hand and chest burns in an X-ray demonstration, was the first of many other reports in *Electrical Review*.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Other experimenters, including Elihu Thomson and Nikola Tesla, also reported burns.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Thomson deliberately exposed a finger to an X-ray tube over a period of time and suffered pain, swelling, and blistering.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Other effects, including ultraviolet rays and ozone, were sometimes blamed for the damage, and many physicians still claimed that there were no effects from X-ray exposure at all.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Despite this, there were some early systematic hazard investigations, and as early as 1902 William Herbert Rollins wrote almost despairingly that his warnings about the dangers involved in the careless use of X-rays were not being heeded, either by industry or by his colleagues.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] By this time, Rollins had proved that X-rays could kill experimental animals, could cause a pregnant guinea pig to abort, and that they could kill a foetus.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] He also stressed that "animals vary in susceptibility to the external action of X-light" and warned that these differences be considered when patients were treated by means of X-rays.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] However, the biological effects of radiation due to radioactive substances were less easy to gauge.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This gave the opportunity for many physicians and corporations to market radioactive substances as patent medicines.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Examples were radium enema treatments, and radium-containing waters to be drunk as tonics.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Marie Curie protested against this sort of treatment, warning that "radium is dangerous in untrained hands".
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Curie later died from aplastic anaemia, likely caused by exposure to ionizing radiation.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] By the 1930s, after a number of cases of bone necrosis and death of radium treatment enthusiasts, radium-containing medicinal products had been largely removed from the market (radioactive quackery).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Only a year after Röntgen's discovery of X-rays, the American engineer Wolfram Fuchs (1896) gave what is probably the first protection advice, but it was not until 1925 that the first International Congress of Radiology (ICR) was held and considered establishing international protection standards.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The effects of radiation on genes, including the effect of cancer risk, were recognized much later.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In 1927, Hermann Joseph Muller published research showing genetic effects and, in 1946, was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his findings.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The second ICR was held in Stockholm in 1928 and proposed the adoption of the röntgen unit, and the International X-ray and Radium Protection Committee (IXRPC) was formed.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Rolf Sievert was named chairman, but a driving force was George Kaye of the British National Physical Laboratory.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] After World War II, the increased range and quantity of radioactive substances being handled as a result of military and civil nuclear programs led to large groups of occupational workers and the public being potentially exposed to harmful levels of ionising radiation.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This was considered at the first post-war ICR convened in London in 1950, when the present International Commission on Radiological Protection (ICRP) was born.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Since then the ICRP has developed the present international system of radiation protection, covering all aspects of radiation hazards.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The International System of Units (SI) unit of radioactive activity is the becquerel (Bq), named in honor of the scientist Henri Becquerel.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] One Bq is defined as one transformation (or decay or disintegration) per second.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] An older unit of radioactivity is the curie, Ci, which was originally defined as "the quantity or mass of radium emanation in equilibrium with one gram of radium (element)".
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Today, the curie is defined as 3.7×1010 disintegrations per second, so that 1 curie (Ci) = 3.7×1010 Bq.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] For radiological protection purposes, although the United States Nuclear Regulatory Commission permits the use of the unit curie alongside SI units, the European Union European units of measurement directives required that its use for "public health ... purposes" be phased out by 31 December 1985.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The effects of ionizing radiation are often measured in units of gray for mechanical or sievert for damage to tissue.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Radioactive decay results in a reduction of summed rest mass, once the released energy (the *disintegration energy*) has escaped in some way.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Although decay energy is sometimes defined as associated with the difference between the mass of the parent nuclide products and the mass of the decay products, this is true only of rest mass measurements, where some energy has been removed from the product system.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This is true because the decay energy must always carry mass with it, wherever it appears (see mass in special relativity) according to the formula *E* = *mc*2.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The decay energy is initially released as the energy of emitted photons plus the kinetic energy of massive emitted particles (that is, particles that have rest mass).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] If these particles come to thermal equilibrium with their surroundings and photons are absorbed, then the decay energy is transformed to thermal energy, which retains its mass.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Decay energy, therefore, remains associated with a certain measure of the mass of the decay system, called invariant mass, which does not change during the decay, even though the energy of decay is distributed among decay particles.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The energy of photons, the kinetic energy of emitted particles, and, later, the thermal energy of the surrounding matter, all contribute to the invariant mass of the system.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Thus, while the sum of the rest masses of the particles is not conserved in radioactive decay, the *system* mass and system invariant mass (and also the system total energy) is conserved throughout any decay process.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This is a restatement of the equivalent laws of conservation of energy and conservation of mass.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Early researchers found that an electric or magnetic field could split radioactive emissions into three types of beams.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Ernest Rutherford named the three types alpha, beta, and gamma, in increasing order of their ability to penetrate matter.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Alpha decay is observed only in heavier elements of atomic number 52 (tellurium) and greater, with the exception of beryllium-8 (which decays to two alpha particles).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Gamma rays are emitted from excited states of nuclei as a side effect of alpha or beta decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Beta decay is the only type to be observed in all the elements.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Lead, atomic number 82, is the heaviest element to have any isotopes stable (to the limit of measurement) to radioactive decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Radioactive decay is seen in all isotopes of all elements of atomic number 83 (bismuth) or greater.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Bismuth-209, however, is only very slightly radioactive, with a half-life greater than the age of the universe by ten orders of magnitude; radioisotopes with extremely long half-lives are considered effectively stable for practical purposes.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In analyzing the nature of the decay products, it was obvious from the direction of the electromagnetic forces applied to the radiations by external magnetic and electric fields that alpha particles carried a positive charge, beta particles carried a negative charge, and gamma rays were neutral.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] From the magnitude of deflection, it was clear that alpha particles were much more massive than beta particles.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Passing alpha particles through a very thin glass window and trapping them in a discharge tube allowed researchers to study the emission spectrum of the captured particles, and ultimately proved that alpha particles are helium nuclei.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Other experiments showed beta radiation, resulting from decay and cathode rays, were high-speed electrons.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Likewise, gamma radiation and X-rays were found to be high-energy electromagnetic radiation.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The relationship between the types of decays also began to be examined: For example, gamma decay was almost always found to be associated with other types of decay, and occurred at about the same time, or afterwards.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Gamma decay as a separate phenomenon, with its own half-life (now termed isomeric transition), was found in natural radioactivity to be a result of the gamma decay of excited metastable nuclear isomers, which were in turn created from other types of decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Although alpha, beta, and gamma radiations were most commonly found, other types of emission were eventually discovered.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Shortly after the discovery of the positron in cosmic ray products, it was realized that the same process that operates in classical beta decay can also produce positrons (positron emission), along with neutrinos (classical beta decay produces antineutrinos).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] These types of decay involve the nuclear capture of electrons or emission of electrons or positrons, and thus acts to move a nucleus toward the ratio of neutrons to protons that has the least energy for a given total number of nucleons.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This consequently produces a more stable (lower energy) nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] A hypothetical process of positron capture, analogous to electron capture, is theoretically possible in antimatter atoms, but has not been observed, as complex antimatter atoms beyond antihelium are not experimentally available.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Such a decay would require antimatter atoms at least as complex as beryllium-7, which is the lightest known isotope of normal matter to undergo decay by electron capture.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Shortly after the discovery of the neutron in 1932, Enrico Fermi realized that certain rare beta-decay reactions immediately yield neutrons as an additional decay particle, so called beta-delayed neutron emission.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Neutron emission usually happens from nuclei that are in an excited state, such as the excited 17O* produced from the beta decay of 17N.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The neutron emission process itself is controlled by the nuclear force and therefore is extremely fast, sometimes referred to as "nearly instantaneous".
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Isolated proton emission was eventually observed in some elements.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] It was also found that some heavy elements may undergo spontaneous fission into products that vary in composition.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In a phenomenon called cluster decay, specific combinations of neutrons and protons other than alpha particles (helium nuclei) were found to be spontaneously emitted from atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Other types of radioactive decay were found to emit previously seen particles but via different mechanisms.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] An example is internal conversion, which results in an initial electron emission, and then often further characteristic X-rays and Auger electrons emissions, although the internal conversion process involves neither beta nor gamma decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] A neutrino is not emitted, and none of the electron(s) and photon(s) emitted originate in the nucleus, even though the energy to emit all of them does originate there.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Internal conversion decay, like isomeric transition gamma decay and neutron emission, involves the release of energy by an excited nuclide, without the transmutation of one element into another.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Rare events that involve a combination of two beta-decay-type events happening simultaneously are known (see below).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Any decay process that does not violate the conservation of energy or momentum laws (and perhaps other particle conservation laws) is permitted to happen, although not all have been detected.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] An interesting example discussed in a final section, is bound state beta decay of rhenium-187.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In this process, the beta electron-decay of the parent nuclide is not accompanied by beta electron emission, because the beta particle has been captured into the K-shell of the emitting atom.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] An antineutrino is emitted, as in all negative beta decays.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] If energy circumstances are favorable, a given radionuclide may undergo many competing types of decay, with some atoms decaying by one route, and others decaying by another.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] An example is copper-64, which has 29 protons, and 35 neutrons, which decays with a half-life of 12.7004(13) hours.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This isotope has one unpaired proton and one unpaired neutron, so either the proton or the neutron can decay to the other particle, which has opposite isospin.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This particular nuclide (though not all nuclides in this situation) is more likely to decay through beta plus decay (61.52(26)%) than through electron capture (38.48(26)%).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The excited energy states resulting from these decays which fail to end in a ground energy state, also produce later internal conversion and gamma decay in almost 0.5% of the time.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The daughter nuclide of a decay event may also be unstable (radioactive).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In this case, it too will decay, producing radiation.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The resulting second daughter nuclide may also be radioactive.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This can lead to a sequence of several decay events called a *decay chain* (see this article for specific details of important natural decay chains).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Eventually, a stable nuclide is produced.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Any decay daughters that are the result of an alpha decay will also result in helium atoms being created.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Some radionuclides may have several different paths of decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] For example, 35.94(6)% of bismuth-212 decays, through alpha-emission, to thallium-208 while 64.06(6)% of bismuth-212 decays, through beta-emission, to polonium-212.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Both thallium-208 and polonium-212 are radioactive daughter products of bismuth-212, and both decay directly to stable lead-208.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] According to the Big Bang theory, stable isotopes of the lightest three elements (H, He, and traces of Li) were produced very shortly after the emergence of the universe, in a process called Big Bang nucleosynthesis.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] These lightest stable nuclides (including deuterium) survive to today, but any radioactive isotopes of the light elements produced in the Big Bang (such as tritium) have long since decayed.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Isotopes of elements heavier than boron were not produced at all in the Big Bang, and these first five elements do not have any long-lived radioisotopes.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Thus, all radioactive nuclei are, therefore, relatively young with respect to the birth of the universe, having formed later in various other types of nucleosynthesis in stars (in particular, supernovae), and also during ongoing interactions between stable isotopes and energetic particles.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] For example, carbon-14, a radioactive nuclide with a half-life of only 5700(30) years, is constantly produced in Earth's upper atmosphere due to interactions between cosmic rays and nitrogen.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Nuclides that are produced by radioactive decay are called radiogenic nuclides, whether they themselves are stable or not.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] There exist stable radiogenic nuclides that were formed from short-lived extinct radionuclides in the early Solar System.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The extra presence of these stable radiogenic nuclides (such as xenon-129 from extinct iodine-129) against the background of primordial stable nuclides can be inferred by various means.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Radioactive decay has been put to use in the technique of radioisotopic labeling, which is used to track the passage of a chemical substance through a complex system (such as a living organism).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] A sample of the substance is synthesized with a high concentration of unstable atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The presence of the substance in one or another part of the system is determined by detecting the locations of decay events.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] On the premise that radioactive decay is truly random (rather than merely chaotic), it has been used in hardware random-number generators.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Because the process is not thought to vary significantly in mechanism over time, it is also a valuable tool in estimating the absolute ages of certain materials.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] For geological materials, the radioisotopes and some of their decay products become trapped when a rock solidifies, and can then later be used (subject to many well-known qualifications) to estimate the date of the solidification.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] These include checking the results of several simultaneous processes and their products against each other, within the same sample.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Thereafter, the amount of carbon-14 in organic matter decreases according to decay processes that may also be independently cross-checked by other means (such as checking the carbon-14 in individual tree rings, for example).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The Szilard–Chalmers effect is the breaking of a chemical bond as a result of a kinetic energy imparted from radioactive decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] It operates by the absorption of neutrons by an atom and subsequent emission of gamma rays, often with significant amounts of kinetic energy.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This kinetic energy, by Newton's third law, pushes back on the decaying atom, which causes it to move with enough speed to break a chemical bond.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This effect can be used to separate isotopes by chemical means.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The Szilard–Chalmers effect was discovered in 1934 by Leó Szilárd and Thomas A.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] They observed that after bombardment by neutrons, the breaking of a bond in liquid ethyl iodide allowed radioactive iodine to be removed.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Radioactive primordial nuclides found in the Earth are residues from ancient supernova explosions that occurred before the formation of the Solar System.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] They are the fraction of radionuclides that survived from that time, through the formation of the primordial solar nebula, through planet accretion, and up to the present time.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The naturally occurring short-lived radiogenic radionuclides found in today's rocks, are the daughters of those radioactive primordial nuclides.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Another minor source of naturally occurring radioactive nuclides are cosmogenic nuclides, that are formed by cosmic ray bombardment of material in the Earth's atmosphere or crust.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The decay of the radionuclides in rocks of the Earth's mantle and crust contribute significantly to Earth's internal heat budget.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] While the underlying process of radioactive decay is subatomic, historically and in most practical cases it is encountered in bulk materials with very large numbers of atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This section discusses models that connect events at the atomic level to observations in aggregate.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Although these are constants, they are associated with the statistical behavior of populations of atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In consequence, predictions using these constants are less accurate for minuscule samples of atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In principle a half-life, a third-life, or even a (1/√2)-life, could be used in exactly the same way as half-life; but the mean life and half-life *t*1/2 have been adopted as standard times associated with exponential decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] where *N*0 is the initial amount of active substance — substance that has the same percentage of unstable particles as when the substance was formed.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The mathematics of radioactive decay depend on a key assumption that a nucleus of a radionuclide has no "memory" or way of translating its history into its present behavior.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] A nucleus does not "age" with the passage of time.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Thus, the probability of its breaking down does not increase with time but stays constant, no matter how long the nucleus has existed.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This constant probability may differ greatly between one type of nucleus and another, leading to the many different observed decay rates.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] However, whatever the probability is, it does not change over time.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This is in marked contrast to complex objects that do show aging, such as automobiles and humans.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] These aging systems do have a chance of breakdown per unit of time that increases from the moment they begin their existence.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Radioactive decay and nuclear particle reactions are two examples of such aggregate processes.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The mathematics of Poisson processes reduce to the law of exponential decay, which describes the statistical behaviour of a large number of nuclei, rather than one individual nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In the following formalism, the number of nuclei or the nuclei population *N*, is of course a discrete variable (a natural number)—but for any physical sample *N* is so large that it can be treated as a continuous variable.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Differential calculus is used to model the behaviour of nuclear decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Consider the case of a nuclide *A* that decays into another *B* by some process *A* → *B* (emission of other particles, like electron neutrinos ν e and electrons e− as in beta decay, are irrelevant in what follows).
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The decay of an unstable nucleus is entirely random in time so it is impossible to predict when a particular atom will decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] However, it is equally likely to decay at any instant in time.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Particular radionuclides decay at different rates, so each has its own decay constant λ.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The negative sign indicates that *N* decreases as time increases, as the decay events follow one after another.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] where *N*total is the constant number of particles throughout the decay process, which is equal to the initial number of *A* nuclides since this is the initial substance.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The number of decays observed over a given interval obeys Poisson statistics.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Now consider the case of a chain of two decays: one nuclide *A* decaying into another *B* by one process, then *B* decaying into another *C* by a second process, i.e.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The previous equation cannot be applied to the decay chain, but can be generalized as follows.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Since *A* decays into *B*, *then* *B* decays into *C*, the activity of *A* adds to the total number of *B* nuclides in the present sample, *before* those *B* nuclides decay and reduce the number of nuclides leading to the later sample.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In other words, the number of second generation nuclei *B* increases as a result of the first generation nuclei decay of *A*, and decreases as a result of its own decay into the third generation nuclei *C*.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The rate of change of *NB*, that is d*NB*/d*t*, is related to the changes in the amounts of *A* and *B*, *NB* can increase as *B* is produced from *A* and decrease as *B* produces *C*.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The subscripts simply refer to the respective nuclides, i.e.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] *NA* is the number of nuclides of type *A*; *N**A*0 is the initial number of nuclides of type *A*; *λA* is the decay constant for *A* – and similarly for nuclide *B*.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The solution can be found by the integration factor method, where the integrating factor is *e*λ*B**t*.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This case is perhaps the most useful since it can derive both the one-decay equation (above) and the equation for multi-decay chains (below) more directly.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] For the general case of any number of consecutive decays in a decay chain, i.e.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] A1 → A2 ··· → A*i* ··· → A*D*, where *D* is the number of decays and *i* is a dummy index (*i* = 1, 2, 3, ..., *D*), each nuclide population can be found in terms of the previous population.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In all of the above examples, the initial nuclide decays into just one product.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Consider the case of one initial nuclide that can decay into either of two products, that is *A → B* and *A → C* in parallel.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] For example, in a sample of potassium-40, 89.3% of the nuclei decay to calcium-40 and 10.7% to argon-40.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] which is constant, since the total number of nuclides remains constant.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] where *N**A*0 is the initial number of nuclide A.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] When measuring the production of one nuclide, one can only observe the total decay constant *λ*.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] because the fraction *λB*/*λ* of nuclei decay into *B* while the fraction *λC*/*λ* of nuclei decay into *C*.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] where *N*A = 6.02214076×1023 mol−1‍ is the Avogadro constant, *M* is the molar mass of the substance in kg/mol, and the amount of the substance *n* is in moles.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] the equation indicates that the decay constant *λ* has units of *t*−1, and can thus also be represented as 1/*τ*, where *τ* is a characteristic time of the process called the *time constant*.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In a radioactive decay process, this time constant is also the mean lifetime for decaying atoms.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] A more commonly used parameter is the half-life *T*1/2.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Given a sample of a particular radionuclide, the half-life is the time taken for half the radionuclide's atoms to decay.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This relationship between the half-life and the decay constant shows that highly radioactive substances are quickly spent, while those that radiate weakly endure longer.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Half-lives of known radionuclides vary by almost 54 orders of magnitude, from more than 2.25(9)×1024 years (6.9×1031 sec) for the very nearly stable nuclide 128Te, to 8.6(6)×10−23 seconds for the highly unstable nuclide 5H.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The factor of ln(2) in the above relations results from the fact that the concept of "half-life" is merely a way of selecting a different base other than the natural base *e* for the lifetime expression.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The time constant *τ* is the *e* −1 -life, the time until only 1/*e* remains, about 36.8%, rather than the 50% in the half-life of a radionuclide.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Since radioactive decay is exponential with a constant probability, each process could as easily be described with a different constant time period that (for example) gave its "(1/3)-life" (how long until only 1/3 is left) or "(1/10)-life" (a time period until only 10% is left), and so on.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Thus, the choice of *τ* and *t*1/2 for marker-times, are only for convenience, and from convention.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] They reflect a fundamental principle only in so much as they show that the *same proportion* of a given radioactive substance will decay, during any time-period that one chooses.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Carbon-14 has a half-life of 5700(30) years and a decay rate of 14 disintegrations per minute (dpm) per gram of natural carbon.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] The radioactive decay modes of electron capture and internal conversion are known to be slightly sensitive to chemical and environmental effects that change the electronic structure of the atom, which in turn affects the presence of 1s and 2s electrons that participate in the decay process.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] A small number of nuclides are affected.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] For example, chemical bonds can affect the rate of electron capture to a small degree (in general, less than 1%) depending on the proximity of electrons to the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In 7Be, a difference of 0.9% has been observed between half-lives in metallic and insulating environments.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] This relatively large effect is because beryllium is a small atom whose valence electrons are in 2s atomic orbitals, which are subject to electron capture in 7Be because (like all s atomic orbitals in all atoms) they naturally penetrate into the nucleus.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] In 1992, Jung et al. of the Darmstadt Heavy-Ion Research group observed an accelerated β− decay of 163Dy66+.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Although neutral 163Dy is a stable isotope, the fully ionized 163Dy66+ undergoes β− decay into the K and L shells to 163Ho66+ with a half-life of 47 days.
[src:nuclear-physics/radioactive-decay-p01] Rhenium-187 is another spectacular example.
